commit_message:
IBP: add GRUB_RECORDFAIL_TIMEOUT for ubuntu

This timeout hasn't been set in default grub2 config.
If a provisioned node experiences unexpected reboot,
grub will refuse to boot after it and will expect for
user input for confirmation.

Setting it to 5secs should help to bypass that confirmation.

This change additionaly allow to set GRUB timeout via config file.

Change-Id: I48af989bc8ad4ccaf2939804614488588010fed2
Closes-Bug: #1465586
(cherry picked from commit 90ab1c79fe9a4fdac155ff872f87e53aaa72d6f7)

commit_message:
Getting of provision data via various sources for fuel-agent

Introduce 'provision_data_uri' flag to let it pulling of provision data from
various sources. Added 2 URI types: 'file://' and 'http://'.
Also it switches to fallback mode, if 'file://' was missing then trying to
interpreter given URI as a file path.

Partially implements: blueprint cobbler-ironic-substitute

Change-Id: I11323171064942ee313e7147159a84318539f38c

commit_message:
Ditch run_as_root kwarg from utils.execute from fuel-agent

Initially fuel-agent was using utils.execute from oslo with
run_as_root kwarg support. Once oslo's utils.execute became
inconvenient for our case, fuel-agent had been switched to custom
made utils.execute wrapper keeping its signature as close as possible
to oslo's one. run_as_root was never used, so it should be removed.

Change-Id: Ic037cbe697fc3912b10f5a7dc9be3eb75b473cc8

commit_message:
IBP: add http_proxy support to fuel-image

Add ability to fuel-image to fetch packages via http proxies.

* pass 'http_proxy' environment variable to debootstrap
* configure proxy per apt repos

Change-Id: I0fc94037259d343a1c3e8d4a6e9d12d93ecb3808
Related-Bug: #1460169

[{'created': '2015-08-14 13:31:56.000000000', 'message': "Add default sorting to the Security Groups table.

The Security Groups table (Project > Access & Security) is initially
ordered by the group's uuid string which makes the table appear to be
randomly sorted. This patch adds a default sorting by the groups'
``name`` attributes.

Change-Id: Ica2831e043e2e7fec8129df4feee93f6c8be3462
Closes-Bug: #1484514
"}]
commit_message:
Add default sorting to the Security Groups table.

The Security Groups table (Project > Access & Security) is initially
ordered by the group's uuid string which makes the table appear to be
randomly sorted. This patch adds a default sorting by the groups'
``name`` attributes.

Change-Id: Ica2831e043e2e7fec8129df4feee93f6c8be3462
Closes-Bug: #1484514

  copy_if_not_exist $SOURCE $TARGET $OWNER
  copy_if_not_exist $SOURCE $TARGET $OWNER

Storwize driver report capability for multiattach

The driver report the capability "multiattach=True"

Implements blueprint: multi-attach-volume

commit_message:
Fix missing parameters in driver CG interface

Clone CG introduced new parameters in the driver CG interface
create_consistencygroup_from_src, but the drivers were not updated
to add the new parameters. This patch adds them for pure.py
and xtremio.py.

Related patch for the VNX driver:
https://review.openstack.org/210319

Change-Id: I5ab121e00179f17408226d470917d165d7e38ddd
Closes-Bug: #1482733

[{'created': '2015-07-30 13:58:58.000000000', 'message': "Don't allow DESTROY on conntrack entries

Prevent the DESTROY action on outbound conntrack entries so
TCP RST's do not take effect on them. For VMs on the same host,
the entry will be cleared as the packet goes through conntrack
again on the other VM's bridge. For VMs outside, the entries will
be left to timeout and expire.

Change-Id: Ibe9e49653b2a280ea72cb95c2da64cd94c7739da
Closes-Bug: #1478925
"}, {'created': '2015-07-31 01:46:10.000000000', 'message': 'Use a conntrack zone per port in OVS

Conntrack zones per network are not adequate because VMs
on the same host communicating with each other cross iptables
twice. If conntrack is sharing the same zone for each cross,
the first one can remove the connection from the table on a RST
and then the second one marks the RST as invalid.

This patch adjusts the logic to use a conntrack zone per port
instead of per network. In order to avoid interrupting upgrades
or restarts, the initial zone map is built from the existing
iptables rules so existing port->zone mappings are maintained.

Closes-Bug: #1478925
Change-Id: Ibe9e49653b2a280ea72cb95c2da64cd94c7739da

commit_message:
Use a conntrack zone per port in OVS

Conntrack zones per network are not adequate because VMs
on the same host communicating with each other cross iptables
twice. If conntrack is sharing the same zone for each cross,
the first one can remove the connection from the table on a RST
and then the second one marks the RST as invalid.

This patch adjusts the logic to use a conntrack zone per port
instead of per network. In order to avoid interrupting upgrades
or restarts, the initial zone map is built from the existing
iptables rules so existing port->zone mappings are maintained.

Closes-Bug: #1478925
Change-Id: Ibe9e49653b2a280ea72cb95c2da64cd94c7739da

commit_message:
Put kube_master into a resource group

With this patch, k8s template support more than one master nodes.
The number of master nodes can be specified through Heat parameter.

For fault tolerance, the cluster tolerants failure of no more than
half of the size. For example, a cluster with 3 master node tolerant
failure of 1 master node. Below is the table:

SIZE TOLERANCE
1    0
3    1
4    1
5    2
6    2
7    3
8    3
9    4

Change-Id: Ic28c13bdcadb39949f9c50be45e09f7627c5d627
Partially-Implements: blueprint make-master-ha

commit_message:
Adds a pep8 target to tox.ini

The will now run flake8 on all Python files and bashate on all shell
scripts. Right now I'm ignoring the bashate errors, since there were so
many of them. Follow up patches will start fixing those issues.

A few Python files had minor modifications to pass flake8.

Change-Id: I5f773eb6ea9f1311aa045951ff9bdad16cca6491

commit_message:
Replace ADFS example DNS name with something appropriate

This replaces the example provided in the keystone defaults
with something more familiar to Microsoft Systems Engineers.

Change-Id: I6c5e13a78a0bb23eef0a86b1a07353a98e793cca
Implements: blueprint keystone-sp-adfs-idp

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html
    Commit Messages: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages"}, {'account_id': 9515, 'date': '2015-07-30 02:47:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-2

The existing wording is correct. Some distributions, particularly Ubuntu, contain an entry in /etc/hosts that resolves the actual hostname (for example, compute1) to 127.0.1.1 instead of a "real" IP address. This causes problems for some services and simply commenting it out resolves them. However, the localhost entry in /etc/hosts that resolves to 127.0.0.1 must remain file for proper operation.'}, {'account_id': 17130, 'date': '2015-07-30 03:00:27.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 17130, 'date': '2015-07-30 05:06:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Install-guide about basic networking.

In the test when localhost(127.0.0.1) is not disable in the host file, there will be shown "Name or Service not known".The existing note is clear about removing or commenting out 127.0.1.1 instead of 127.0.0.1.

Fixed bug #1459742

Change-Id: If484a506b027537f3de658f9156f102caff30f5a

Hi Oleg,
I'm working on the patch https://review.openstack.org/#/c/123815/ (which has dependency on 122024). This one takes care of manual move of router from one l3-agent to another.
I tried your patch, it is not handling the router move from one l3-agent to another.

Does your patch is handling the case if one of the Network node hosting the router goes down, the router reschedule function reschedules the router to another Network node? I tried this use case with your patch, but not able to see the qrouter and snat name space getting created in the Network Node which is up.

Ila."}, {'account_id': 1131, 'date': '2015-07-08 21:21:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 5948, 'date': '2015-07-09 10:13:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)

@Ila, I'll still have to test manual rescheduling, will come up with results soon. As for auto rescheduling, did you apply both this and parent patch https://review.openstack.org/#/c/199032.
I tested it and it seems working fine, here is the scenario:
 - 2 controllers with neutron servers and l3 agents in dvr_snat mode; 1 compute with l3 agent in dvr mode;
 - vm running on a subnet connected to a dvr router
 - vm can ping external net
 - router is scheduled to all three l3 agents
 - take down dvr_snat agent on the node hosting snat
 - wait while rescheduling happens (depends on agent down_time config) by monitoring l3-agent-list-hosting-router and see when xxx agent will be removed from the list
 - snat namespace should be created on the second node with dvr_snat agent
 - vm can still ping external net
 - bring back down dvr_snat l3 agent
 - snat_namespace is deleted by the agent since it's not hosting the router any more
 - vm can still ping external net
Can you please try the same and tell which step fails for you?

I've executed this scenario several times by taking up/down dvr_snat agents in rotation."}, {'account_id': 5948, 'date': '2015-07-09 10:15:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

One thing to add is that I applied and tested both this and parent fixes on a stable/kilo environment. I didn't notice any significant changes in DVR since Kilo, please correct me if I'm wrong."}, {'account_id': 5948, 'date': '2015-07-09 12:49:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

This patch should be coupled with https://review.openstack.org/#/c/122024 in order for manual rescheduling to work'}, {'account_id': 10076, 'date': '2015-07-09 23:23:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

@Oleg: I applied the patch 122024 on top of 199032 and applied 199032 on top of 199514. Now your agent side patch 199514 was having both 199032 and 122024 patches.
With this setup I tried the router manual move (using the command neutron l3-agent-router-remove and neutron l3-agent-router-add), it didn't work. I noticed it is not entering either external_gateway_removed or external_gateway_updated conditions. Due to this the snat namespace is not getting deleted from the network node.

Also I tried your scenario of bringing down the network node hosting the snat. I have the report_interval = 30 and agent_down_time = 75 in /etc/neutron/neutron.conf. When the agent that is hosting the snat goes down, i do see the command l3-agent-list-hosting-router having xxx, but i'm not seeing the entry getting deleted or the snat namespace getting created in the other network node (waited for around 10 mins). Is there anything I'm missing in the steps?"}, {'account_id': 5948, 'date': '2015-07-10 07:51:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

@Ila, 199032 and 199514 was enough for auto rescheduling to work in my env, have you tried them without 122024? Can you please also look through the logs of neutron server and both dvr_snat l3 agents for any errors/traces? I guess it's something on the server side since you're seeing xxx agent not being deleted from l3-agent-list-hosting-router results. This means rescheduling was not triggered.

Today I'm going to apply 122024 on top of my patches to see what's wrong with manual rescheduling. Will come up with results shortly."}, {'account_id': 5948, 'date': '2015-07-14 07:33:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Ok, with https://review.openstack.org/#/c/122024 (+ a fix described below) on top of this one and it's parent I was able to manually remove and add dvr router from/to a dvr_snat L3 agent. snat namespace is removed and added as expected. 

The key fix was to update router gateway port binding info (before passing it to agent) on router remove, so agent sees gw port difference and calls external_gateway_updated(). I will probably proceed with a new patchset on https://review.openstack.org/#/c/122024"}, {'account_id': 10076, 'date': '2015-07-14 17:29:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
DVR: fix router rescheduling on server side

This fixes router rescheduling for dvr routers to
correctly handle CSNAT portion rescheduling on server side.

Next patch will make L3 agent aware of possible SNAT role
rescheduling to/from it.

Partial-Bug: #1472205
Change-Id: I069500a2f1de9a734124544a3f2d793e9fa2d27c

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to

commit_message:
DVR: do not reschedule router for down agents on compute nodes

Scheduling/unscheduling of DVR routers with l3 agents in 'dvr' mode
running on a compute nodes is done according to DVR serviced ports
created/deleted on that compute nodes. It doesn't make sense to reschedule
router from l3 agent on compute node even if it's down - no other l3 agent
can handle VMs running on that compute node.

Closes-Bug: #1470889
Change-Id: Ib998b9e459dd1a9ab740fafa5d84dc3211ca0097

condition handle resources, due the implementations are

commit_message:
Fix ValueError when doing cluster_scale_in action

If a cluster contains no nodes, ValueError happens when
trying to scale-in the cluster. This patch fixes this bug.

Change-Id: I6094cdeecdd42c842176427a2a373783bcf843a8
Closes-Bug: #1485535

Now here use the meat attribute 'pagination_param'
marker = self.request.GET.get(
             tables.PackageDefinitionsTable._meta.pagination_param, None)

commit_message:
Fix package view.py use wrong table meta attribute

Now here use the meat attribute 'pagination_param'
marker = self.request.GET.get(
             tables.PackageDefinitionsTable._meta.pagination_param, None)
But this meta attribute define in the tables as 'prev_pagination_param'

This patch fix it

Change-Id: Id129863fbe7492b77e6c0e6e737b8d9d2932bd0a

commit_message:
Rely on autorequire for config resource ordering

Currently we specify the ordering of config resources wherever it is
necessary based on the presence of the file it will write to, or the
presence of the package in charge of providing the file it will write
to.

Those kind of ordering can be specified directly at the resource level
using the autorequire mechanism. With this patch, any config resource
will make sure the package in charge of providing the file will be
installed first.

Change-Id: Icb3464cc0a747d40326d610d38806d059c9a0fc3

commit_message:
Don't return Exception when volume is detached

This patch changes the way we handle volume detach
attempts when the attachment_id is already detached
and/or when the volume has no attachments.  We now
handle this the same way we do with deleting volumes
that don't exist.  We return success.

This patch also takes care to make sure we safely reset
the volume status to what it should be depending on if
there are other attachments.  If the attachment_id is
passed in and that attachment is detached, but there are
other attachments, we want to make sure that the volume is
left in an in-use state, not available.

Change-Id: I11b7c45bb6570ce11e13e487cf1136ca2551036b
Closes-Bug: #1484194
Related-Bug: #1476806

commit_message:
Add multipath support to 3PAR iSCSI driver

Adds multipath support to the 3PAR iSCSI driver.

target portals, iqns and luns will be returned if multipath
is being used.

Also adds a new function 3par common that allows finding
of all existing VLUNs.

Implements: blueprint 3par-iscsi-multipath-support
Change-Id: I6b17cc9057eaf726b6a31921fd8a141c5a430d52

Just want to document the discussion that has happened in IRC yesterday:  It appears that there was a misunderstanding of how the empty ("") policy was being used.  We should not have been using it.  

Cory has concerns that we are working around the real bug by updating the default policy setting.  There may be a bug at the DB API layer that needs to be further investigated.  

So, I think we really need to start by getting this merged.  We have a hole here and it needs to be plugged.

I have opened this bug to cover improving the policy settings:  https://bugs.launchpad.net/cinder/+bug/1477621

A bug to look at limiting access at the DB API layer is here:  https://bugs.launchpad.net/cinder/+bug/1477625

If there are no objections to this approach I will merge this patch later today.'}, {'account_id': 11904, 'date': '2015-07-23 14:49:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 4159, 'date': '2015-07-23 15:01:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Set default policy for "volume:get"

Currently, there is no policy check defined for "volume:get", so
everyone can get another tenant's volume detail by UUID. It's necessary
to set policy to "rule:admin_or_owner" for "volume:get" by default.

Change-Id: Iefdf7e5703a28856b20d97a885267c01bed6bbb4
Closes-bug: #1475422

commit_message:
Fix crendential type problem in webhook operations in client side

Remove dict type in Webhook Model since crendential value in response body
is no longer in dict form.

Change-Id: Ia441483dd20f38b28200ff814bb0963a8548a1f2
Closes-Bug: #1485830

commit_message:
Update SHAs for kilo development

The upper cap on pbr is breaking builds and the Heat fix has been
appropriately backported to stable/kilo. This updates the SHAs so kilo
development can work as expected.

Closes-bug: 1485751
Change-Id: Ibe271e86b3df107436b2f21703c231cadf6c3249

commit_message:
Activate pep8 check that _ is imported

Remove the specification in tox.ini that _ is a builtin so that
it will no longer assume that _ does not need to be imported.
This helps ensure that the _ from i18n is used.

Activating this check did not flag any violations.

Change-Id: Ibb45131025bb64feb26d3c2fd596fe2b07c0b889

commit_message:
Fix HP3PAR extra-specs scoping prefix bug

The recently added HP 3PAR extra-specs for create share options
use the wrong prefix for scoping. The prefix should not have used
an underscore in it. In addition, the underscore used in the docs
was different than in the code.

The new scoping prefix will be "hpe3par" (to be followed by a colon
for scoping or underscore for future capabilities).

Fixes Bug: #1481106

Change-Id: Ibd326fc367c1845e56706969daf01359fa7b2dac

ironic/drivers/modules/irmc/common.py had several contributors, not sure you can just assign your company copyright here. please check other files as well (you can use github).'}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2015-08-14 09:40:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Dmitry,

I don't think Naohiro should add copyright lines for companies he does not work for. Other contributors that contributed with that code could extend the copyright line if they wish so."}, {'account_id': 10239, 'date': '2015-08-14 09:41:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

To me adding a copyright line to an existing file means stating it's an IP of Fujitsu, which is not true (any more). I think we need legal advice on this matter."}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2015-08-14 09:49:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

There are plenty of files where only the original author(s) has a copyright line i.e [1]. I think it's fine if Fujitsu wants to add a copyright line for the modules they have contributed with (others vendors/individuals can do as well if they wish so).

I wish they were added when the module was first introduced. And I even think that it's a valid argument if we say that patches *only* adding copyright lines won't be allowed. But currently we don't have any consensus on that.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/ironic/blob/master/ironic/conductor/rpcapi.py#L3-L3"}, {'account_id': 10239, 'date': '2015-08-14 09:52:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

> There are plenty of files where only the original author(s) has a copyright line

I'm not sure it's a correct argument. People contributing afterwards *choose* not to add their copyrights. Here Naohiro just applies his company copyright on top of other's work. I don't know if it's legal or not."}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2015-08-14 09:57:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Right, so let's seek for legal advice in the legal-discussion mail list [1] and let's try to get a consensus within the Ironic group about it before we actually merge this patch

(changing vote until a consensus is made)

[1] http://lists.openstack.org/cgi-bin/mailman/listinfo/legal-discuss"}, {'account_id': 13719, 'date': '2015-08-17 01:01:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Lucas, Dmitry,

Thank you for sparing your time and reviewing this patch.

Of course, I didn't mean that Fujitsu has *exclusive* copyright to those files, but the initial commit.

It seems there is a minimum consensus that an initial commit can have copyright at least, because [1] doesn't have any (-1) vote.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/171672/

Therefor I'll resubmit 3 patches to add copyright to the initial commits for iRMC power, management, and deploy drivers respectively. 
Each commit message will specify that the copyright notice is for the initial commit with commit number.

Then I'll abandon this patch if we can agree this solution.

What do you think?

Best regards,
Naohiro"}, {'account_id': 13997, 'date': '2015-08-17 01:22:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

Naohiro, looks good, nice catch!'}, {'account_id': 13719, 'date': '2015-08-17 02:17:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Workflow-1

Lucas, Dmitry, Mitsuhiro,

Thanks for the review, Mitsuhiro.

 > Therefor I'll resubmit 3 patches to add copyright to the initial commits for iRMC power, management, and deploy drivers respectively.

I've submitted the 3 patches, please find them.

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/213572/
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/213575/
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/213577/

Best regards,
Naohiro"}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2015-08-17 09:58:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Hi Naohiro,

Isn't it better to just keep this one? And, gerrit is going to merge the change against master so there's no way we can actually apply things to the "initial commit".

Since this patch already got a discussion going on I think we are better of continue with it? Breaking this patch in three will just scatter the conversation across multiple patches.'}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2015-08-17 18:06:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

Thanks @devananda for checking it out!

<devananda> short answer from clarkb in infra re: (c) headers on https://review.openstack.org/#/c/212973/ -- copyright headers always get stale, but if the original contributor wants it added, it doesn't matter, and it's fine"}, {'account_id': 2889, 'date': '2015-08-17 18:14:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

While it's best to have the attribution headers in the first patch introducing a body of code (assuming that the contributing author wants the attribution line there at all), it is my understanding that this is not necessary from a legal POV. The CLA already includes both the license grant to the project and the attribution to the contributor via the git commit history.

However, since the files being modified here were originally written by Naohiro Tamura, and this patch is also being proposed by Naohiro, I have no objection to this attribution header being added.

FWIW, I also checked with Clark:

18:02:38 < devananda> (c) header question for folks -- if a vendor/driver author "forgot" to add the (c) lines in their files early on and wants to do it now, is there any reason to object?
18:02:47 < devananda> patch in question: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/212973/
18:03:41 < clarkb> devananda if its accurate data and the holder eants it I dont think so, but they do tend to get stale over time'}, {'account_id': 5805, 'date': '2015-08-17 19:29:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

Naohiro, I agree with Lucas' comments on the split out patches. This one patch is fine for this.

Thank you Deva for looking into this issue with infa."}, {'account_id': 13719, 'date': '2015-08-18 00:54:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Workflow

Lucas, Devananda, Chris,

I greatly appreciate the comments on this issue and the confirmation to the infra team.

I abandon the three patches, so please merge this patch.

Best regards,
Naohiro'}, {'account_id': 10343, 'date': '2015-08-18 01:03:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

commit_message:
Add copyright notice to iRMC driver source code.

This patch adds copyright notice in accordance with "APPENDIX: How to
apply the Apache License to your work" [1].
Also this is a reflection of the gerrit review comment in [2] that is
there's no problem adding a copyright line in the license header in
OpenStack.

[1] http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0
[2] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/171672/

Change-Id: Ic0d69c735170267640803a9bc707f058306c9da1

commit_message:
Make the Config class be a singleton

Fixes the Config class so that is behaves as a singleton.
six.add_metaclass should be used as a decorator on the class.

Add a unit test to verify correct behavior.

Closes-Bug: 1485672
Change-Id: I3535704ec399a303a8178c0c6803b89682ca096f

commit_message:
Moving inline html code out of transfer-table.spec.js

Currently there are some html code for test hard-coded inside of spec.js
file. It would be much better to move them out to separate html file for
better readability, cleaner spec code. This will also enable the sharing
html mock code between specs. This is possible due to the new auto-file-
colleting mechanism.

This patch moves inline html code out of transfer-table.spec.js.

Change-Id: I6e560d65299612f2ea8f5e48c71b4c366fe32222
Partial-Bug: #1485134

[{'created': '2015-08-17 21:11:18.000000000', 'message': 'Remove hardcoded bridge name in bonded compute NIC config

This change removes a hardcoded value for the bond name in the NIC
config for the compute node in the bond-with-vlan NIC config
templates. When this hardcoded value of "br-bond" is used, then the
Neutron bridge mappings must be set to set to datacentre:br-bond in
order for VLAN mode networking to recognize the bridge. By using the
input value for bridge_name we will ensure that the controller and
compute nodes have the same bridge name (defaults to "br-ex"), and
that the defaults will work with VLAN mode.

Change-Id: I28654ab93e3c10a8597c8b877f3f2f6b3eca887c
'}]
commit_message:
Remove hardcoded bridge name in bonded compute NIC config

This change removes a hardcoded value for the bond name in the NIC
config for the compute node in the bond-with-vlan NIC config
templates. When this hardcoded value of "br-bond" is used, then the
Neutron bridge mappings must be set to set to datacentre:br-bond in
order for VLAN mode networking to recognize the bridge. By using the
input value for bridge_name we will ensure that the controller and
compute nodes have the same bridge name (defaults to "br-ex"), and
that the defaults will work with VLAN mode.

Change-Id: I28654ab93e3c10a8597c8b877f3f2f6b3eca887c

commit_message:
Switch from deprecated timeutils.isotime

oslo_utils.timeutils.isotime() is deprecated as of 1.6 so we need
to stop using it.

This patch replaces timeutils.isotime(dt) with dt.isoformat() as
the deprecation message suggests in oslo_utils.timeutils.
However this might be a backward incompatible change as
timeutils.isotime() produced '1955-11-05T18:00:00Z' format
but datetime.isoformat() produces '1955-11-05T18:00:00+00:00'
format.

Change-Id: Ied2643d3d891600e0e5cd31c7ef1ff6107e3a777

@Kevin, your proposal is good for the logging case, but there are use cases where i want to extend the security group rules with more actions/possibilities, that way just referencing it might be a bit complicated.

For example, cases where order of the rules is important, which is another problematic behaviour.

I personally don't understand the disagreement to support optional security groups extensions and we also offered a spec to this in a generic way .

This spec https://review.openstack.org/#/c/151247/ describe this way and one possible use case which enable an important east-west brute force prevention"}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2015-06-11 20:51:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

Those are all changes to the security group API. If you can get general agreement from everyone to abandon the EC2 API, then I'm fine with extending it. 

Logging doesn't require changing the sg API so I don't see why it's necessary for this patch."}, {'account_id': 11343, 'date': '2015-06-12 07:00:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

@Kevin,

I am afraid that we might find ourself (if we start doing it like that) with all kind of different tables referencing the security group and adding complexity. 

If i take your suggestion, i would like to see a "generic" table added which can be extended to other features and have logging as one of its options/features, and that structure can reference the security group

Yushiro, If this sounds reasonable to you and to Kevin (and others), i can help with defining a spec for this and helping with the code.
(I believe its very similar to the suggestion we already made, but instead of using an extension to the security group extension, we add a different structure which reference it)
And then  logging is one use case of that.'}, {'account_id': 4656, 'date': '2015-06-13 00:59:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

@Sean, @Kyle, @Gal, @Kevin

However,  I'd like to use logging API for Firewall same as Security-group.

I'd like to discuss following contents:

1. Logging API form
2. How to specify the log target: security-group or security-group-rule, firewall or firewall-rule.

Could you please give me some comments?

> It appears your theory that v3 URL works with empty version string in public/internal endpoints is mistaken.

> --os-auth-url http://127.0.0.1:5000 --os-identity-api-version 3 seems to fail regardless of what's advertised in the catalog.

Are you using password auth or token auth?  If you are using password auth, are you also providing the user domain and project domain?"}, {'account_id': 9983, 'date': '2015-08-13 17:35:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

I don't think there is anything special about the endpoint, whether it is public, admin, or internal.  I think the main thing is the type of authentication, and whether osc can infer what type of authentication the caller wants to use.

I think the reason this patch may be working for you is that in your testing, the only client using the admin url is the puppet-openstack keystone.rb provider, which uses token based auth.  Since osc cannot infer from the token what url you want to use, you have to specify the url path "/v2.0" or "/v3".  For password based auth, osc will use "/v3" if you provide OS_USER_DOMAIN_[NAME|ID] or OS_PROJECT_DOMAIN_[NAME|ID] or are getting a domain scoped token.  Otherwise, it will use "/v2.0".

I think we need some clarification from the osc guys.  Steve, would you say that the above is an accurate assessment of how osc works with respect to Keystone authentication?'}, {'account_id': 6525, 'date': '2015-08-13 21:35:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

This is not theory of mine, I'll add the pointers to the code later.

This is effectively working for OSC but not only, any client would too.
This is not the case for the service token (admin endpoint, or 35357 port by default), not providing the version for this one breaks clients."}, {'account_id': 9983, 'date': '2015-08-13 21:42:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

> As far as I've been told, it's different behavior between os-auth-url and os-url.

Then this patch should not be concerned with public url vs. admin url, it should be concerned about when OS_AUTH_URL is used vs. when OS_URL is used?  That is, it is possible that someone may use OS_URL with the public url, and may use OS_AUTH_URL with the admin url.

What I mean to say is that there should not be a version suffix anywhere, even on admin url.  What clients use admin url that need the suffix?  Can we fix them?  I think that would be the better approach, if this bug/patch is to be addressed at all, which brings up another point: is it necessary to do this at this time?  I know that once we convert all of the puppet modules to v3, to use the keystone authtoken middleware properly, it will be easy to switch to versionless urls.

> Although the doc [1] says it should be versionless for both it breaks clients if the admin url doesn't have the version

Which clients?  I think we really need to identify which clients need the version in the url.

> but the goal is to get rid of version in the URLs.

There still needs to be some logic somewhere that knows if you want to get a token you can use either /v2.0/token or /v3/auth/token.  Many clients (python, osc) try to hide this complexity as much as possible, some don't do such a good job."}, {'account_id': 6525, 'date': '2015-08-14 03:38:57.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-08-14 03:56:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified-1

The public endpoint (and internal when derived from it) can support both API
versions 2.0 and 3. To do so the URL must not be suffixed with the version.

Although the keystone documentation doesn't reflect it yet, this has been
confirmed by Keystone developers and as a matter of fact works. Effectively,
Keystone will automatically adjust to either versions depending on the context.

For instance, using the default values will create the following catalog:
keystone identity RegionOne
  publicURL: http://127.0.0.1:5000
  internalURL: http://127.0.0.1:5000
  adminURL: http://127.0.0.1:35357/v2.0

"}, {'created': '2015-08-15 13:38:25.000000000', 'message': "Endpoints without API version and refactored auth

1. All endpoints support API versions 2.0 and 3 without specifying the version.

Although the keystone documentation doesn't reflect it yet, this has been
confirmed by Keystone developers and as a matter of fact works. Effectively,
Keystone will automatically adjust to either versions depending on the context.

For instance, using the default values will create the following catalog:
keystone identity RegionOne
  publicURL: http://127.0.0.1:5000
  internalURL: http://127.0.0.1:5000
  adminURL: http://127.0.0.1:35357

2. Admin endpoint is used to build os-url in a fail back case where there is no
other URLs available for authenticating. This is typically the case
when bootstrapping, nothing is available yet. Refactoring those methods brings
better readibility and should help maintain it.

So this patch does bring:

- No API version in URL path, unless neede (see below)
- Refactors the 'get' endpoints methods
- Makes sure the API version is present when using the service_url (os-url) and
for user password validation

This might be broken down in smaller pieces if needed.

Change-Id: Id94967df9e507fa62d6f135a4470d07564f5ba8f

So this patch does bring:

- No API version in URL path, unless needed (see below)
- Refactors the 'get' endpoints methods
- Makes sure the API version is present when using the service_url (os-url) and
for user password validation

This might be broken down in smaller pieces if needed.

commit_message:
Endpoints without API version and refactored auth

1. Purely cosmetic change on keystone provider
Reorders methods in alphabetical order for better readability and anticipating
coming changes.

2. Admin endpoint is used to build os-url as fail back when they're no others
URL available for authenticating. This is typically the case when bootstrapping,
where no users/roles are available yet. Refactoring those methods brings better
readability, troubleshooting and to help maintain it.
- Refactors the 'get' endpoints methods
- Makes sure the API version is present when using the service_url (os-url) for
user password validation

3. All endpoints support API versions 2.0 and 3 without specifying the version.
Per keystone documentation [1]. Although the main Openstack wiki pages might not
reflect this entirely. Effectively, Keystone automatically adjusts to either
versions depending on the context.

For instance, using the default values will create the following catalog:
keystone identity RegionOne
  publicURL: http://127.0.0.1:5000
  internalURL: http://127.0.0.1:5000
  adminURL: http://127.0.0.1:35357

For easier and faster validation, this review has been broken down into smaller
pieces. It will allow 1. and 2. to be back-ported to Kilo:
1. https://review.openstack.org/213598
2. https://review.openstack.org/213603
3. https://review.openstack.org/213957

[1] https://github.com/openstack/keystone/blob/master/doc/source/http-api.rst

Change-Id: Id94967df9e507fa62d6f135a4470d07564f5ba8f

commit_message:
Combine multiple YAMLs into single YAML

This commit combines the contents of the
three YAML files (for Glance, Heat and
Murano assets) into a single file
called assets.yaml. It also modifies
the javascript for the website so the
site will load the assets.yaml file
instead of the three individual YAML
files.

Change-Id: Ia004e6d4f3b51ca853945b136abdc1599d7af4b8
Implements: blueprint expand-asset-types

commit_message:
Implement a yaml formatter in cliff

This change replaces the cliff-tablib yaml formatter with an internal
replacement. It differs from the tablib formatter in the following ways:
- always outputs with block formatting rather than the PyYAML default
  of deciding based on value content
- emit_one serialises a simple dict where the column name is the key
  and the data item is the value (rather than a list of dicts with
  'Field' and 'Value' keys)
- emit_one preserves column order by printing a single-item dict for
  each column_name

The cliff release which contains this change will need a corresponding
cliff-tablib release which removes the yaml formatter from its setup.py
entry_points.

Change-Id: I691dbab3dee7c5ec28b1083f87ab1f5c051d582b
Related-Bug: #1308744

commit_message:
Support time-delays in server.resize

Resize operation in nova(that we are for flavor update) is
asynchronous. So the server may be ACTIVE when we are checking
server-resize operations(not RESIZE as was excepted).
We need to wait for a while till the server becomes RESIZE.

The patch add support of this case to Server resource in heat.
Closes-bug: #1471135

Conflicts:
	heat/tests/test_instance.py
	heat/tests/test_server.py
(cherry-picked from commit f46af8a8e2daa52f6485d65da4ad69db6f0a32bd)

Change-Id: I19914081996104c5f2144a6de795173f26774c21

commit_message:
Move extensions to separate method in NovaClient

Move getting extensions to method _get_extensions
in NovaClientPlugin and fix tests for it.

Closes-bug: #1482153

commit_message:
Add base_attributes_schema to documentation

Currently base_attributes_schema omitted in docs,
so there's no chance to learn about base attributes.
This patch adds base_attributes_schema to docs and
fixes description of "show" base attribute.

Change-Id: Id382e39401d368367f1813e7f9e4508d4dffef72
Closes-bug: #1484142

commit_message:
Remove test for job type in get_data_sources

There is an explicit test for job type in get_data_sources() with
an early return, but for all job_executons input_id and
output_id will be set to None on creation if they are not present
and data_source_get() will return None when the id is None. So, the
explicit test is not needed -- remove for easier maintenance.

Change-Id: I36f59d9fdb3cde923d09e17af346cff8b518eb8e

commit_message:
Add pyinotify to global-requirements.txt

This module is needed for oslo.log library.

Is the library actively maintained? -Yes.
https://github.com/seb-m/pyinotify/commits/master.
Is the library good code? -Yes.
Is the library python 3 compatible? -Yes.
Is the library license compatible? -Yes. It uses MIT license.
Is the library already packaged in the distros we target? -No.
Is the function of this library already covered by other libraries
in ``global-requirements.txt``? -No.


License of lib is MIT. It is Python 3 compatible.

Change-Id: Ia7eafdc31438c625716adfcdd17d6af72a361919

commit_message:
go: replicator rewrite

The replicator no longer uses HTTP, really.  It uses HTTP to set up a
TCP connection, then does a simple json protocol over it for replication.

We're just tired of fighting with go's Expect: 100-continue handling.

See doc.go for details on the protocol.

Change-Id: I007beadc7c1682cca91f6bc389c1319713cc6f04

This is a good idea, but needs a little work in order to function in multi-region clusters with high-latency WAN links between regions.

Instead of (a) make a request for remote time, (b) get local time, (c) compare, how about (a) start = local time, (b) make request for remote time, (c) end = local time, (d) check start <= remote <= end? That way, if you have a globe-spanning Swift cluster, you don't get false positives from swift-recon."}, {'account_id': 16896, 'date': '2015-07-09 10:14:42.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 16896, 'date': '2015-07-09 10:15:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Nice job!"}, {'account_id': 330, 'date': '2015-07-22 15:51:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

(4 comments)

I think this is a great patch, technically. It's got a small scope, it tests the added functionality, and it updates the docs (even the manpages!). I've got some questions inline about the precision of the checks and the reporting.

It's not clear to me *why* this is needed. Checking time sync in the cluster is nice, but the data's timestamps are set on the proxy server, not the storage servers. And recon only is on the storage servers. So what benefit are we getting from checking that the storage servers are time-synchronized? I guess it's good to check, but that doesn't seem to be where it's nearly as important as the time sync on the proxies.

This is definitely a very soft -1 from me. I'd like some clarity on what's being done and why. And if a problem is discovered, then we can find a better answer.

Thanks for the patch!"}, {'account_id': 330, 'date': '2015-07-22 16:05:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: -Code-Review

Ok, after being reminded of some things in IRC, yes the storage nodes need to be in sync too. So that answers the overall "why" question sufficiently for me.

I'd still like clarity on the reporting precision.'}, {'account_id': 7233, 'date': '2015-07-23 03:06:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1

commit_message:
Time synchronization check in recon.

This change add call time to recon middleware and param --time to
recon CLI. This is usefull for checking if time in cluster is
synchronized.

Change-Id: I62373e681f64d0bd71f4aeb287953dd3b2ea5662

commit_message:
Add dashboard folder and graphite dashboard to doc

Create a dashboard folder to hold HTML files that provide
dashboard views into various parts of neutron.  This allows
the dashboards to be "living code" rather than frozen in
amber via shortened URLs.

The first dashboard example is a simple HTML file that
shows thumbnails of graphite plots of all neutron jobs
in the check pipeline.  Clicking a thumbnail brings up
the larger graphite plot page.

Change-Id: I47e7718c2aae41c8308fd331377984e47a892294
Signed-off-by: Ryan Moats <rmoats@us.ibm.com>

commit_message:
Do not require the token_id for converting v3 to v2 tokens

Requiring the token_id as part of the arguments for converting v3 to
v2 tokens results in a more difficult transition to the unification
of the code paths for issuing and validating V2 tokens. This is the
first step in eliminating similar but not-quite the same code paths
for issuing and validating Fernet V2 tokens and all other forms of
V2 tokens.

Change-Id: I348974c8285a1a7b724aee1bfbf2d694d5d77406

subject: Maintain the expiry of v2 fernet tokens

commit_message:
Maintain the expiry of v2 fernet tokens

The v2 fernet provider didn't carry the expiration of a token from it's
parent token when handling a rescope. This means that a rescope of fernet
tokens could extend the session indefinitely.

Change-Id: Id1ec725fd89cd32260b7be4eead24a0fc84abfe1
closes-bug: #1469563

commit_message:
Add copyright to the initial commit of iRMC deploy driver code.

This patch adds copyright notice to the initial commit [1] of iRMC
deploy driver source code in accordance with "APPENDIX: How to
apply the Apache License to your work" [2].
Also this is a reflection of the gerrit review comments in [3] that is
there's no problem adding a copyright line in the license header in
OpenStack, and in [4] that is there is a minimum consensus of initial
commit copyright notice.

[1] commit f55ab34e54cffd10b263db6d74e2669e75de6e4b
[2] http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0
[3] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/171672/
[4] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/212973/

Change-Id: I1a3c2cdbf3aa2c6b4d16a12f6ef6b7bf1dbb983e

commit_message:
tests: Do not skip IPv6 tests

Namely:
    test_router_update_gateway_upon_subnet_create_ipv6
    test_router_update_gateway_upon_subnet_create_max_ips_ipv6

They no longer need to be skipped after the recently merged
neutron change. [1]

They have been skipped by overriding with no-op methods
in our class.  This commit un-skip them by removing the
overrides.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/198420/

Change-Id: Idb6dd3c80b833a53cfa9da9139078eaefcde8c6b

'}]
commit_message:
Add copyright to the initial commit of iRMC power driver code.

This patch adds copyright notice to the initial commit [1] of iRMC
power driver source code in accordance with "APPENDIX: How to apply
the Apache License to your work" [2].
Also this is a reflection of the gerrit review comments in [3] that is
there's no problem adding a copyright line in the license header in
OpenStack, and in [4] that is there is a minimum consensus of initial
commit copyright notice.

[1] commit 4412b83481343304f2f1bc5c4da4b65d8dc1a9ed
[2] http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0
[3] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/171672/
[4] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/212973/

Change-Id: Iec6ab4128f33f4eecc730626172f2e2d06eb0a2c

commit_message:
Add image tag specification in dev-quickstart.md

Now starting kolla by using command: sudo ./tools/kolla-compose start.

It will raise an exception like:
"compose.progress_stream.StreamOutputError: Tag latest not found in
repository docker.io/kollaglue/centos-rdo-rabbitmq".

We should let user know to change tag in yaml file according the tags in
hub.docker.com

Change-Id: I30bed869ae5da0825b201bc3c0a49d8c1496e87d
Closes-Bug: #1485521

commit_message:
Updated master for new dev work - 15 Aug 2015

This patch updates all git SHA's to the current head of
the appropriate branches.

This patch includes the upstream fix for CVE-2015-5163:
 - https://review.openstack.org/212567

This patch removes the configuration for the cryptography
repository as they have now released tag 1.0 which contains
the SHA we required for fernet tokens to work.

Change-Id: Iaab3a9d1007ccae6d51942fe045e274b7a518e9f
Closes-Bug: #1484766

commit_message:
Remove compose from documenation

Receive several quickstart related questions every day.  Make a
first pass at cleaning up our documentation to point people
in the right direction.  While we are about it remove compose
related bits.  Anything in the compose directory will remain as
a reference implementation for how to implement the compose
files to work well with our container content.

Change-Id: I9e832e97ac2bacca8eab7e1bfbd82664d2b191b8
Closes-Bug: #1485163
Paritally-Implements: blueprint remove-config-internal

[{'created': '2015-06-24 07:25:09.000000000', 'message': "Validate string, integer limit for input parameter

1. If you pass name or description parameters with more than
   255 characters to the below apis, then it returns
   500 error code.
   a. consisgroup-create
   b. consisgroup-update
   c. cgsnapshot-create
   d. quota-class-update
   e. quota-update
   f. qos-create

2. If you pass 'hard_limit' value above mysql INT type to below
   apis, then it returns 500 error code.
   a. quota-class-update
   b. quota-update

3. Below apis accept string with whitespaces,
   a. consisgroup-create
   b. cgsnapshot-create
   c. qos-create

Added a check to validate string and integer limit and returned
400 if limit exceeds. Also added check to remove leading or trailing
whitespaces and string containing only whitespaces.

APIImpact
1. For all above apis 400 response will be returned.
2. Earlier is was possible to pass only whitespaces or leading-trailing
   spaces to name parameter. Now it will raise 400 error if
   only whitespaces are passed or remove leading-trailing spaces
   from name.

Closes-Bug: 1466351
Closes-Bug: 1463379
Closes-Bug: 1465967
Change-Id: I0c0029d61ba2b293b579d1afffec0bdf062b22a8

commit_message:
Validate string, integer limit for input parameter

1. Below apis will return 500 error code on passing name or description
   parameters with more than 255 characters:
   a. consisgroup-create
   b. consisgroup-update
   c. cgsnapshot-create
   d. quota-class-update
   e. quota-update
   f. qos-create
   g. volume-manage
   h. volume-transfer

2. Below apis will return 500 error code on passing 'hard_limit' value
   greater than mysql INT type:
   a. quota-class-update
   b. quota-update
   c. encryption-type-create

3. Below apis accept name as string with whitespaces:
   a. consisgroup-create
   b. cgsnapshot-create
   c. qos-create
   d. volume-transfer

4. Type-key api will return 500 error code on passing key or value with
   more than 255 characters.

Added new method
1. validate_name_and_description() in
   cinder.api.openstack.wsgi.Controller to validate length of name and
   description and returned 400 if it exceeds the limit and removing
   leading or trailing whitespaces and string containing only
   whitespaces.
2. validate_string_length() in cinder.api.openstack.wsgi.Controller to
   validate length of string and returned 400 if it exceeds the limit.
3. validate_integer() method in cinder.utils to validate integer
   limit and returned 400 if limit exceeds.

APIImpact
1. For all above apis 400 response will be returned.
2. Earlier it was possible to pass only whitespaces or leading-trailing
   spaces to 'name' parameters and 'key' while updating key-value in
   type-key api.
   Now it will raise 400 error if only whitespaces are passed and will
   remove leading-trailing spaces if present in other cases.

Closes-Bug: 1466351
Closes-Bug: 1463379
Closes-Bug: 1465967
Change-Id: I0c0029d61ba2b293b579d1afffec0bdf062b22a8

needs to be able to upload merge commits for review.

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-08-06 06:55:14.000000000', 'message': 'Remove rally-jobs job group

This job group is not really needed, in all cases a single job of
the group is needed and never the whole group.

Instead add to each repository the single job that is used.

commit_message:
Remove rally-jobs job group

This job group is not really needed, in nearly all cases a single job of
the group is needed and never the whole group.

Instead add to each repository the single job that is used.

Exception: rally itself uses most of the job group, add all used jobs to
it.

This change is just a cleanup, it should not have any side effects on
which jobs run.
It reduces the number of created Jenkins jobs from 6521 to 6464 since
many unused jobs are not generated anymore.

Change-Id: I0a309aa975dccefbcc111c28a12aad9872681dcb

remove keystone extensions from openstackclient functional job

the extensions are enabled by default now, so we no longer need
to specify them in the functional job.

Change-Id: Iec52acddf8ffee7edd70ef7aa7cf3922b0df17e3

commit_message:
Create an os-testr venv for running subunit2html

This commit creates a venv for installing os-testr which will enable
all test jobs to have access to the subunit2html utility which has
been moved to live inside the os-testr package instead of as a slave
script.

Change-Id: I2050b54eb2def10438764f3eeb55ecf9caa874dc

commit_message:
Change functional testing to use clouds.yaml

Using clouds.yaml, instead of sourcing openrc, we can have better
functional testing by distinquishing between an admin account
and a normal user account.

We cannot both source openrc AND use clouds.yaml as this confuses
the inventory functional tests, and is not a recommended way of
utilizing o-c-c, anyway.

In order for these test to work, a bug fix was needed in
os-client-config, so the requirements was bumped to 1.6.2
or higher.

Depends-On: I6458969b45f5534e1172b9f8ba598d7c536a59b5
Change-Id: If459afba3cf61b3c7f641c79494cd53a682666a4

commit_message:
Horizon linting should be voting

Now that horizon JS linting issues are resolved, it is time to make it voting.
This patch remove the lines that make this job non-voting.

Change-Id: Ic31e6b8c197f98ae9533d50c6361b5ff6f8121f9

commit_message:
Drop these config switches as they are no longer being used

The project-config job using these switches is being dropped,
and since the referenced bugs look to be addressed, we can
clean up these as well.

Change-Id: I00d99c05328268b33c6f20b1d24e7507afccb92c
Depends-on: I886f64a2379a8e16957e6ca4bcf784cb22ad2c28

commit_message:
Fix 'OS-EXT-VIF-NET' extension missing in v2.1 -Kilo

V2 API has extension for virtual interface 'OS-EXT-VIF-NET'
but it is not present in v2.1 API. Because of this there is
difference between v2 and v2.1 response of virtual interface API.

v2 List virtual interface Response (with all extension enable)
{
    "virtual_interfaces": [
        {
            "id": "%(id)s",
            "mac_address": "%(mac_addr)s",
            "OS-EXT-VIF-NET:net_id": "%(id)s"
        }
    ]
}

v2.1 List virtual interface Response
{
    "virtual_interfaces": [
        {
            "id": "%(id)s",
            "mac_address": "%(mac_addr)s"
        }
    ]
}

Attribute  "OS-EXT-VIF-NET:net_id" is missing in v2.1

This was somehow missed during the v2.1 implementation because
there was no functional tests for virtual interface API in v2.1.
This was found during merging of functional tests between
v2 and v2.1 - I7097483cb57ed785b01fddb4f832e453f71987fd

As v2.1 APIs are released in Kilo, this commits fix this issue
in kilo stable branch.

Fix in master branch - I289f21f9e42fff95d8ea68fbaefc9bec166b9540

Also this commit adds functional tests in v2.1 and merge unit tests
between v2 and v2.1

Change-Id: I7939bf1b63c98eb17bc8bdc4711f56c81f4da08d
Closes-Bug: 1470690

commit_message:
Fix 'OS-EXT-VIF-NET' extension missing in v2.1

V2 API has extension for virtual interface 'OS-EXT-VIF-NET'
but it is not present in v2.1 API. Because of this there is
difference between v2 and v2.1 response of virtual interface API.

v2 List virtual interface Response (with all extension enable)

{
    "virtual_interfaces": [
        {
            "id": "%(id)s",
            "mac_address": "%(mac_addr)s",
            "OS-EXT-VIF-NET:net_id": "%(id)s"
        }
    ]
}

v2.1 List virtual interface Response

{
    "virtual_interfaces": [
        {
            "id": "%(id)s",
            "mac_address": "%(mac_addr)s"
        }
    ]
}

Attribute  "OS-EXT-VIF-NET:net_id" is missing in v2.1
This was somehow missed during the v2.1 implementation because
there was no functional tests for virtual interface API in v2.1.

This was found during merging of functional tests between
v2 and v2.1 - I7097483cb57ed785b01fddb4f832e453f71987fd

This commits fix the v2.1 to have same response as v2 virtual interface
API with 'OS-EXT-VIF-NET' extension enabled.

Also this commit fix functional tests and unit tests to run the same tests
against v2 and v2.1

Change-Id: I289f21f9e42fff95d8ea68fbaefc9bec166b9540
Closes-Bug: 1470690

commit_message:
Puppet-dashboard is read only now

This software hasn't been used for some time and its original upstream
has been dead for a while. Puppetborad largely replaced this. Let it
rest in peace.

commit_message:
libvirt: use instance UUID with exception InstanceNotFound

Ensure that the UUID is used when using the exception. A instance
name is not unique.

Note: This is follow-up of commit 8845b6558af7764b6bfcdf092b64c285ff3716c2,
make sure we fix that in all places.

Change-Id: I9355024cdd95a78968e2acea3278c5d492902c64

commit_message:
Register alembic_migrations at install time

This allows neutron-db-manage to find the alembic migrations
automatically if this project is installed.

The config file alembic.ini is not needed in this project since it's
tables are in neutron's DB and so it depends on neutron's config.

Remove the l2gw-db-manage script since we will use
neutron-db-manage.

Update the alembic env to know about all neutron core tables when
generating diffs for --autogenerate.

Partial-Bug: #1470625

Depends-On: I9a06de64ce35675af28adf819de6f22dc832390d

Change-Id: I581932d333e378d91d5b581760018ec274330681

commit_message:
Removing refrence to bind_requested flag

During Ironic mid-cycle, we decided that this
flag is not needed. Instead, we will use host-id
for this purpose. When the port does not
need to be bound, host-id will be set to None.
Neutron (ML2 plugin) already has a mechanism to
deal with this. Therefore, it was decided that
we do not need two ways to accomplish one action.

Change-Id: I7936fd7545a4672042b32e1c941798f7b5dd1272

commit_message:
Minimal setuptools required for tests

pkg_resources.RequirementParseError has been introduced in
setuptools 16.0. That's the minimal version for running tests.

Change-Id: I4ee2d60a48b4b783d65a7516d794c69c86e4c334

because it is under case of unsupported db backend.

So if the users need the original out-of-order action list, I think I can add url param to implement it in other patch, but it need real use case.

Yingxin's suggestions sounds reasonable when there are many tables and rules in one complex policy.

commit_message:
Ordered datasource actions list

Sorts the datasource actions list API result,
list all actions order by action name so that
the users can find out the action easily.

Change-Id: I055b4ac975eb9757e8f6cf6b8b239fedaf9fe449

commit_message:
Do refactor for neutronv2 driver

Aims to keep consistence of datasource driver state,
and avoid the conflict between datasource row list and
datasource updating state. Do some refactor for
neutronv2 driver, use a temporary state to collect row data,
then override the self.state table one by one.

This is a demo for getting some feedback from other reviewers.
If the way is approved, same refactor will been implemented on
all other datasource drivers by following the pattern.

Change-Id: I74102f35ca16b82419de145a5263eb5d135e82a3
Partial-Bug: #1473924

commit_message:
Add update_state in DataSourceDriver

Implements common logic about updating state in
DataSourceDriver class, and call it in decorator
@check_raw_data_changed_and_update_state in order
to help the subclass datasource drivers to update
self.state automatically when they use the decorator.

Change-Id: Ib296ad0f32a2cb924e27d036eb0e644e00bfdc16
Partial-Bug: #1473924

commit_message:
Allow stack sudo in nodepool dsvm job

The nodepool job can't build dib images without giving the nodepool
process (running as stack) sudo rights. Go ahead and allow the stack
user to sudo in this job since we don't need to test rootwrap here.

Once this gets in the work to add dib image builds in the dsvm test
can proceed.

Change-Id: I304ac3732eb57723e5bfc584cc1e3a2e5a0667ab

commit_message:
Bump websockify to 0.6.1

0.6.1 is a minor bugfix that closes an open security bug.  Force 0.6.1 as the
minimum version.

Change-Id: I3aeb3b80d56594c919b5b55229f71fda7fb79587
Closes-Bug: 1447675

Update Alembic to 0.8.0

Neutron needs the latest alembic version to support contact/expand
autogeneration as part of online migration support.

Partially-Implements: blueprint online-schema-migrations

commit_message:
Bump version of bandit to 0.13.2

The latest version of bandit 0.13.2 includes many fixes over the
previous 0.10.1.  This will help many projects that are currently
using bandit and possibly reduce some configuration issues with
their bandit.yaml.

Change-Id: I5f51cd5c9832e5efb46fd08f937051e1efb80557

[{'created': '2015-08-14 10:57:19.000000000', 'message': "Bump pecan to 1.0.0

Neutron is introducing a Pecan WSGI server. However, its URIs
have segments which, despite being compliant with RFC 3986 cannot
be handled by pecan 0.8 as they're not valid python identifiers
names.

This patch proposes a bump to 1.0 in order to ensure that all
valid characters for RFC 3986 can be specfied in pecan route
segments.

Note: both ubuntu (vivid) and fedora (23) do not package pecan 1.0.
However, this is true also for several openstack libraries, and
being pecan a former stackforge project the same exception
made for libraries such as oslo-db might apply to Pecan as well.

Change-Id: I858b54c8fbc7037d11fd58846a817d955ed2c5f8
"}]
commit_message:
Bump pecan to 1.0.0

Neutron is introducing a Pecan WSGI server. However, its URIs
have segments which, despite being compliant with RFC 3986 cannot
be handled by pecan 0.8 as they're not valid python identifiers
names.

This patch proposes a bump to 1.0 in order to ensure that all
valid characters for RFC 3986 can be specfied in pecan route
segments.

Note: both ubuntu (vivid) and fedora (23) do not package pecan 1.0.
However, this is true also for several openstack libraries, and
being pecan a former stackforge project the same exception
made for libraries such as oslo-db might apply to Pecan as well.

Change-Id: I858b54c8fbc7037d11fd58846a817d955ed2c5f8

commit_message:
Bumg python-manilaclient version to 1.2.0

Manilaclient of versions below 1.2.0 uses already removed old
'oslo' namespace and does not work because of it. So, bump it to lowest
version that uses new namespaces.

Change-Id: I971a82c45f90e490190553f681d5c61ba924924e

commit_message:
Bump gabbi to version 1.1.4

Ceilometer has used gabbi, but version 0.12.0 cannot support build tests
with prefix. build_tests() method didn't has prefix parameter in
version 0.12.0, see [1]

[1] https://github.com/cdent/gabbi/blob/master/gabbi/driver.py#L62

Change-Id: I4103d15f8c350fe4a9e3e3c0f74de160dc94426e

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

[{'created': '2015-06-19 20:09:36.000000000', 'message': 'Preserve DVR FIP rule priority over Agent restarts

IP rule priorities assigned to DVR floating IPs need
to be preserved over L3 agent restarts. Such a
 mechanism is already in place for Link Local IP
address allocation.

This change generalizes the allocation management
mechanism used for managing Link Local IP addresses
and utilizes it for managing floating ip rule priorities.

The ItemAllocator class is used as base clase for the
classes LinkLocalAllocator and FipRulePriorityAllocator
which in turn provide the allocator objects for each
use case.

Change-Id: I6a75aa8ad612ee80b391f0a27a8a7e29519c3f8d
Co-Author-By: Rajeev Grover <rajeev.grover@hp.com>

commit_message:
Preserve DVR FIP rule priority over Agent restarts

IP rule priorities assigned to DVR floating IPs need
to be preserved over L3 agent restarts. Reuse
the ItemAllocator class decomposed from Link Local IP
address allocation.  Also move commn unit tests to
ItemAllocator class.

Closes-Bug: #1414779
Change-Id: I6a75aa8ad612ee80b391f0a27a8a7e29519c3f8d
Co-Authored-By: Rajeev Grover <rajeev.grover@hp.com>
Co-Authored-By: Ryan Moats <rmoats@us.ibm.com>

commit_message:
Tacker API extension for NFV MANO

This specification describes the new 'vnfm' extension that will be added
to Tacker v1 REST API based on ETSI NFV MANO standards.

Change-Id: I1fc345df2ce7d67c83bda6e2ed3fe5d6c5049f35
Blueprint: tacker-api-mano

commit_message:
Neutron base does not need python-neutron-client package

There is no such package.  It is called python-neutronclient.

Since we know deployments work well without this dependency,
might as well just remove the error since it pops up in the
gating.

Change-Id: Ic0daf85201cf283ee0560a9905e5079e421efbc4
Partially-Implements: blueprint gate-source-builds

NSX plugin: Moving away plugin extensions

out of the neutron repository.

Related-Blueprint: core-vendor-decomposition

commit_message:
Fix oslo_messaging package name for default log level

Since the oslo namespace was dropped in the oslo.messaging
library, we need to fix the package name as well.

Closes-Bug: #1484501
Change-Id: Ibcc8868dcb39f82421369e212e527449cb0e49c5
(cherry picked from commit b5f32bb0e1bb7d77b8034164359f0be2bbe4b6d9)

commit_message:
Fix oslo_messaging package name for default log level

Since the oslo namespace was dropped in the oslo.messaging
library, we need to fix the package name as well.

Closes-Bug: #1484501
Change-Id: Ibcc8868dcb39f82421369e212e527449cb0e49c5

commit_message:
Add "port(s)" to "Ports binding ext attr"

This is a bug similar to https://bugs.launchpad.net/openstack-api-site/+bug/1480312,
which has been confirmed.  A patch for the bug has already been merged.

"Request parameters" and "Response parameters" tables of "Ports
binding extended attributes" are missing "port(s)" (xsd:dict). Please
see http://developer.openstack.org/api-ref-networking-v2-ext.html#port_binding-ext .

I also did some refactoring on common.ent to make it more maintenance
friendly.

(DF): Ran spell-check on common.ent and did more clean-up.

Change-Id: I7986945eea6b98b7fb26d32a275ef6a5635c14b7
Closes-Bug: #1482245

  union_all: ~10.9s

with ~300k traits... so yeah... i'm actually surprised it isn't a bigger gap."}, {'account_id': 6537, 'date': '2015-06-16 09:35:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Workflow-1

Hi Gordon,

Just a few quick questions. What do you mean by longer queries? Also how much will this be useful if we introduce default limit on events too?

Best Regards,
Ildiko'}, {'account_id': 6537, 'date': '2015-07-02 13:40:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

i think it mandatory limits will limit this effect but i think it's still a performance plus and not negative.

just for reference, to ensure uniqueness already, the primary key is set to event_id+key, so we can never have the same trait for an event.

commit_message:
use union all when building trait query

union all is more performant as it doesn't need to filter out
duplicates. we should not have duplicates as the primary key
conditions already ensure that.

Change-Id: Ic25f7086b33a98ca77a669732a65be5a95b7f0db

commit_message:
Change default install type to binary

Currently set to "rdo", however rdo is merely a symlink in the tree and
the default in build.py is "binary".

https://github.com/stackforge/kolla/blob/67ce01fc625ace5ebef72951fdf59b63af0e9ea6/tools/build.py#L147

Change-Id: Ic17a4f83064173fa9297bc0f92deda11a143a1be
Closes-Bug: #1485739

commit_message:
Add required property to Opt class

In order to validate options, it's important to know which are required
and which are not. Add the required field so that such information can
be expressed.

Change-Id: I9c377dedd87533b556efa3acb3aa3416d65d9769

commit_message:
Remove the iSCSI rescan during disconnect

Doing an iSCSI rescan at disconnect time is pretty
dangerous to do.  iSCSI rescan doesn't make volumes
go away, it makes them show back up.  So during Nova
live migration it will make local scsi volumes show
back up.

Nova live migration first loops over volumes and calls
disconnect_volume, then after that it loops over the volumes
again and call's cinder to terminate_connection.

If disconnect_volume does a rescan, then volumes there were
removed during previous calls will show back up, because cinder's
driver hasn't had a chance to terminate the connection yet
from the array.

Closes-Bug: #1483326
Change-Id: I8708db16a4b9057b09abad9f956fa5a3bb4ba54c

commit_message:
Call pypowervm LPAR Wrapper validation on deploy

The additional validation in pypowervm will catch and raise
deployment violations that the PowerVM management interface will raise.
This is done to avoid issuing failing calls to the management interface.

There is still several validation checks needed in pypowervm.
Currently the validation will check that the LPAR desired processors
will not exceed what's available on the host.

Additional validation checks to be implemented in pypowervm:
1. Memory validation
2. Deploy vs resize validation

Change-Id: I3db3ada41e43da52072eaaf4eef3592668e05c8f

(1 comment)

Hi Akihiro,

The problem with storing a MAC address in a neutron port is that the port must be attached to a network when it is created. However, at the point in the workflow that the MAC address is being recorded (server being physically installed), the admin doesn't know the network or tenant it will belong to. The external port is a place for this MAC to be held until the server is actually assigned to a tenant and the tenant decides what network to put it on. Does that make sense?


With regard to tenant_id, I preferred to use it so the enforcement of ownership/visibility was automatically handled by the API layer. If I change it to assigned_tenant then I will have to write code to handle all of that. To address your concern about creating/deleting, how about I just set the policy for deleting to admin_only?"}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2014-06-02 17:46:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Add spec for neutron-external-attachment-points

Adds the specification for the neutron external
attachment points extension to integrate external
devices (e.g. baremetal instances) into a neutron network.

Change-Id: Ieea08993f364415c56e3416b1d222101ce5d1ac9

commit_message:
Make it possible to not remove stack sudo

In cases where we are using devstack plugins to test services against
devstack that are not openstack services we may want to allow those
services to have sudo access. Prior to this change this was not possible
as d-g always removed the stack users sudo rights.

Add a flag that continues to disable sudo by default but allows for
stack user sudo access when appropriate.

Change-Id: I78ebf6432e9ea680cdb8bf103967cf9ed6c1b401

commit_message:
Avoid from storing samples with empty or not numerical volumes

In some cases Ceilometer receives notifications with 'counter_volume' equal
None, for ex. from glance when empty image was created. This patch adds check
to avoid storing samples with None or not numerical volumes.

Closes-Bug: #1484117
Change-Id: Ic4b87c05d16dba765f601ca346b198eda7c91bea

commit_message:
Make heat build from source in the templates

There was an error during docker-templates for heat.  I think
I copied keystone's example rather then looking at our from
source reference.

Change-Id: Id073ce0b0d9e72acb3b752f49a2b8cfcd5d51851
Partially Implements: blueprint docker-templates

commit_message:
Make gnocchi-base build from source

gnocchi-base requires the gcc c++ compiler to build panda, whatever
that is.

Paritally-Implements: blueprint gate-source-builds

commit_message:
Adds support to Mon publisher to archive on error

When publishing metrics to Monasca-api fails, the
failed metrics need to be handled in some manner,
otherwise risk data loss.

Currently, Ceilometer notification agent does not
support requeuing of samples on publisher error.

This patch adds the ability to enable metrics
archival (via conf) using FilePublisher in Ceilometer.
This ability is switched off by default.

Change-Id: I482d4466ae106e5292d12a768e8acd4a240f4049

commit_message:
Make ssh commands stateless

This makes our ssh-into-test-instances commands completely stateless. That
means they accept any key automatically (which we already did) and not
write them out to the known_hosts file of the user running grenade. Without
this, multiple runs of grenade (or existing host keys for the IPs we use)
will conflict and cause us to fail when validating things over ssh because
of the key mismatches.

Change-Id: I0be425764cd640ada4f00300167df77fd870214e

commit_message:
Add header guard to functions/functions-common

To avoid sourcing this twice and getting globals mixed up,
particularly when using multiple plugins, add a "header guard" that
ensures we only source it once.

In general I don't think functions/functions-common have been written
or considered to be idempotent.  I don't think going down that path is
going to be a long-term solution as it's easy to break.

Change-Id: Idca49eb996d2b7ff3779ec27ed672a2da7852590
Closes-Bug: #1469178

commit_message:
libvirt: enable virtio-net multiqueue

Add supoort to enable the virtio-net multiqueue feature for guest
instances.

With virtio-net multiqueue enabled network performance can be scaled
accross number of vCPUs, by transfering the packets through multiple virtqueue
pairs at a time.

When the feature is enabled, the Libvirt driver will set the number of queues
equal to the number of guest VCPUs.

To enable this feature, the following should be set in the Glace image
properties:

    hw_vif_multiqueue_enabled=true

DocImpact
Partially Implements blueprint libvirt-virtio-net-multiqueue

Change-Id: I8505cb71de2cf9d771fa1fe9eddce3d39158e74f

commit_message:
Add X509KeyPair controller and conductor.

This patch adds X509KeyPair controller and conductor to handle all
x509keypair related operation and also add test for it.

Change-Id: I5773fcd5bdf8a30fd195714e3e0fdc9d1b0c962d
Partially-Implements: bp secure-kubernetes

commit_message:
Add GenericKeyManager (example) implementation of CertManager

This is very rough and quick, has no tests, and may have bugs -- but it
is only intended to be an example of how simple it would be for
literally any HSM to support the CertManager interface. This is not
inteded to merge as-is.

Change-Id: Ie3a57ba8b145bc5a0f4432e5a3dc2ae22d98ac45
