This is a trivial change that masks a considerable amount of controversy as to exactly what a certificate manager should look like.
(including how this should be handled in v2).

Castelan was originally envisioned as an interface to provide the basic interfaces that a key storage device would need.  So its something that both a KMIP device or the KRA or Barbican would use.

The fact that Barbican provides Certificate containers is barbican specific (and is also accidental).  In fact, there will be efforts in
v2 to more cleanly delineate the distinction between the two.

The changes you are proposing requires a spec where you clearly define what you want to accomplish in CartManager and justify why that should be in Castellan.'}, {'account_id': 10273, 'date': '2015-08-12 20:04:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Ade, you are correct in that this does the job of setting a goal without really detailing the why or how. The how can be seen in the next CR in the chain, of course, but I do realize that the "why" is equally important (or possibly moreso). I have explained in bits and pieces, but I don't think I've ever adequately set down the high level "grand vision" I have for Certificate handling in Openstack. Here's a very high level overview:

There are many uses in Openstack for Certificates. People use them to serve web traffic with services like Apache/lighttpd/etc running on Nova VMs. People use them to do TLS offloading on Neutron-LBaaS Load Balancers. People use them for VPN or Firewall applications (which are also upcoming projects in Openstack). People currently can store and order Certificates in Barbican. 

The thing these uses all have in common is that they utilize both an X509 Certificate, a Private Key, an optional Intermediates Chain, and an optional Private Key Passphrase. The current Openstack Certificate Ordering Process (via Barbican) returns a container (or "Certificate Bundle") in an appropriate format to be used in this manner. The current Openstack Secret Storage Process (via Barbican) also supports storing this bundle in this format.

The *vision* is that users can simply and easily Order, Store, Use and Reuse these Certificate Bundles by passing around a single simple href to any service that supports it (LBaaS is the first, but I hope that VPN/FWaaS would follow, and HEAT could easily implement support for this in templates for creating WebServers). We could finally have a system that makes dealing with Certificate Bundles *easy*.

This really only requires one thing to get going: a solid and concise definition of a Certificate Bundle that can be easily utilized in any service. I believe Castellan is the place to do that, and this is my attempt. If we codify what an "Openstack Certificate Bundle" is, early and simply, I think it's possible this could work.'}, {'account_id': 10273, 'date': '2015-08-12 20:29:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Just a couple of examples I found, showing that this concept of Cert/PK/PKP/Intermediates is fairly standard:

https://www.digicert.com/ssl-certificate-installation-barracuda.htm

https://docs.openvpn.net/how-to-tutorialsguides/administration/installing-and-managing-ssl-web-certificates-in-openvpn-access-server/

https://www.digicert.com/ssl-certificate-installation-apache.htm'}, {'account_id': 10273, 'date': '2015-08-12 20:35:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

"The fact that Barbican provides Certificate containers is barbican specific (and is also accidental)."

^^ It shouldn't be accidental. We should make sure that the storage of this *commonly used together set of data* should be possible in Barbican, and as I have said about 1000 times now and explained I THOUGHT very thoroughly, this can be done in *ANY SYSTEM* that allows storing arbitrary data. I can even make a generic implementation that would work with *any key storage backend* that is selected, by using the Castellan key interface!'}, {'account_id': 10850, 'date': '2015-08-12 20:41:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

There is always the risk in OpenStack to start just another project. Castellan is for secrets, project  is for certificates, etc. but since as Adam showed they are connected concepts it makes sense to have one project to handle them both and therefore cut back on the users/developers confusion rating out of the sheer number of occasionally overlapping projects.'}, {'account_id': 8623, 'date': '2015-08-12 20:43:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Adam, in those examples you posted, it still looks like the different certificate parts are uploaded as individual items and no bundle is used. I agree that if you are going to use certificates you need the different parts like the cert, the private key, and CA bundle, but I think you can still use all those things using 3 different calls to retrieve all items instead of bundling them.'}, {'account_id': 10273, 'date': '2015-08-12 20:48:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Kaitlin: If the general consensus is that the usability improvement is so trivial between this method and having no logical grouping system, then I guess I would have to cede to that view. Personally, I think there are numerous advantages to a logical grouping, not the least of which is that as a user you can more easily keep track of which Secrets link with what. If I have 20 Private Keys and 60 different X509 Certs that go with them, and passphrases for them and Intermediates for them -- how the heck do I keep track of that easily as a user?'}, {'account_id': 11628, 'date': '2015-08-12 22:18:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I see a lot of value in this.  PKCS12 is commonly used for passing around collections of certs, keys, and intermediates in the file based world (it's the primary file format for export/import on Windows).  Taking that idea into the OpenStack world with hrefs is a great idea.  It would really simplify the user experience for setting up/managing LBaaS TLS offload and VPNaaS.
More and more the intermediate cert chain is growing, so allowing services such as LBaaS and VPN act on a single entity that contains all of the required content makes sense.
Anyway, I am in support of seeing folks working on this and fleshing out the details."}, {'account_id': 10273, 'date': '2015-08-12 23:05:27.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-08-12 23:14:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

When I said that certificates were added to Barbican by accident, what I actually meant was that the certificate functionality was grafted onto existing Barbican functionality (ie. a secret store) that is not always conducive.

The v2 version of the API will seek to redress some of the pain points here - in particular, it will be possible to deploy barbican without CA interfaces exposed, and certificates will no longer be represented as a collection of secrets.

The idea of representing cert bundles as a collection of secrets is quite strange for a number of reasons -- certs and intermediates are supposed to be public (not secret), more often than not private keys never leave the client where they are generated, intermediates can change etc.

The new version of the API will have a certificate object that contains the cert, intermediates (which maybe would be fetched anew, as they may have changed?), private key reference and passphrase (if available) etc.

In particular, the private key/passphrase reference could be a reference to a secret contained in another barbican instance altogether.  The main point though is that the private key and passphrase are the only things that are stored as secrets.

These are all Barbican considerations.  What does this mean for castellan?

I fully agree that there should be an interface to exchange the kind of information that would be exposed in a PKCS12 structure.  There are obvious cloud case use cases for this.  The question is whether this should be part of castellan.

The original raison d'etre for castellan was to provide an interface for the storage/retrieval of secrets that could be implemented by secret storage devices (like a KMIP device).  

Within this framework, I could also see the potential for retrieving collections of secrets -- although even that is problematic as I'm not sure KMIP devices support containers.  Whats an even further stretch though is supporting collections of objects, some of which are secrets and some of which are not.

If we want to change the scope of what castelan does to include certificate bundles - and I'm not opposed to that because for this might make the transition from v1 to v2 more manageable, and also so that folks would not need a new project -- then I would expect the new interface to be a more comprehensive certificate related interface including operations such as issuance, revocation, renewal, maybe encryption of the private key with a client defined password.
I would also want to see a data structure that more clearly defines what a cert bundle looks like.

I understand that you've separated the CertManager from the CertGenerator, but this distinction makes no sense to me -- how could something be a CertManager and not a CertGenerator?  Well, I see how you've done it -- but this example seems a little artificial to me."}, {'account_id': 10273, 'date': '2015-08-13 18:05:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

In the same way that for a long time, Barbican was a CertManager and not a CertGenerator, and in the way that a KMIP device or an LDAP server could be a CertManager or a CertGenerator. In the way that Anchor can be a CertGenerator but not a CertManager.

 I think it's actually much rarer that something does both the generation and the storage of certs. 

Also, there is nothing preventing us from changing Barbican to no longer store certs/intermediates as Secrets, and instead store them as metadata on a privateKey or something, for example. I don't like this a whole lot, because then you can't as easily have one privateKey with a multitude of certs, but as an example, we could still support that with this same interface, just the implementation changes a little bit. I think people are getting caught up on imagined restrictions and not focusing on the big picture."}, {'account_id': 10273, 'date': '2015-08-13 18:08:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

As for privateKeys not leaving the client, that is not true at all for the use cases we're solving for. Every use case I've listed would absolutely require private keys to be stored in the KeyManager/CertManager."}, {'account_id': 10273, 'date': '2015-08-13 18:10:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

"although even that is problematic as I'm not sure KMIP devices support containers"

Ade, I swear, if I have to debunk this for the 100th time, I am going to go insane. T_T'}, {'account_id': 10273, 'date': '2015-08-13 18:16:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Patch Set 3 was rebased'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-08-13 18:35:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

Ade: See https://review.openstack.org/#/c/212701/ for an example of how trivial it would be to support this in any available KeyManager backend.

Alternatively, it would be possible as well to do a split-backend implementation, if you just wanted to store the PrivateKey and Passphrase in the KeyManager, and then had a DB or something configured to store the Certificate and Intermediates, and the overall linkage.'}, {'account_id': 10273, 'date': '2015-08-13 20:27:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

So far I see relatively few comments on or arguments against the actual *interface*, but rather most of the concerns are around specific implementations (and assumptions made about their modes of operation).'}, {'account_id': 9914, 'date': '2015-08-13 20:53:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

In practice, the split backend thing is roughly what would happen in Barbican v2, even if its under the covers.  That is, certs, intermediates and linkages would end up being stored in the database for instance, while keys would be stored in the SecretStore.

From what you've said, it seems to me that:

1. CertManager is basically an interface for storing and retrieving PKCS12 (or their associated data) objects.  As such this is a very cert (as opposed to secret) specific interface.  

I think this is a useful thing to have, and its worth considering what (if any) search capabilities this might have -- Can you search for a bundle based on cert?  Or by private key?

2. If its in castellan, its an extension of what we has stated castellan to be -- a generic interface for secret storing devices.  So arguments like -- KMIP doesn't do this -- no longer apply.

If folks are OK with extending Castellan as in (2), then we can move forward with discussing how the interface should look."}, {'account_id': 7973, 'date': '2015-08-14 03:49:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

While I agree that grouping a cert + key + whatever else you need to get TLS running is valuable, I'm not convinced that it belongs in Castellan.  I think that this change expands the scope of Castellan to store the mapping of the cert + key + etc.

But the main purpose of Castellan is to provide an interface for projects that want to be able to be deployed on clouds that can't run Barbican.  We expect such clouds to be using some other key manager system like a PKCS#11 or KMIP device.

I think this interface would complicate the deployment of such clouds.  The way I understand the LBaaS use case is that the user is responsible for storing all the separate pieces into the key manager system, then making the bundle (container) and then passing the bundle reference to LBaaS.  If the cloud is not using barbican, then the operator has to figure out a way to store that association somewhere.  It's not a hard problem to solve, but it does complicate the deployment.  We could store the bundle data in the device itself, but that seems like it's a misuse of a key manager device.

We would also need to provide some service to make the creation of bundles easy for the user since they would need to be stored in the device first so the bundle reference can be made available to LBaaS.  This interface would also add a second type of plugins to Castellan, further complicating deployment.  I don’t think adding all this complexity is necessary since we can avoid it by asking the user to pass the separate pieces to LBaaS and use the current Castellan implementation instead.

I should also point out that containers are already supported in Barbican, and another option would be to take a hard dependency on Barbican instead of adding this interface to Castellan."}, {'account_id': 10273, 'date': '2015-08-17 19:22:00.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

The issue Doug raises is a valid one -- unless Castellan becomes a SERVICE (which is unarguably outside any intended scope) there's no way to use the interface as an *end user* to store stuff, which means there's no way for it to enforce its own container system. In that case, this proposal is dead in the water. RIP Castellan-Certs."}]

commit_message:
VMware: Deprecate vCenter version less than 5.1

Log a warning if the vCenter server version is less than 5.1.
The plan is to enforce the version in M release.

DocImpact
Running Cinder with a VMware vCenter version less than 5.1 is
deprecated. The minimum required version of vCenter server will
be raised to 5.1 in the 8.0.0 release.

Change-Id: I38f520cace67ddcaf067787683ac47f50a6c0b3f

commit_message:
OpenStackProvider: Refresh IPs before looking for access IP

Change I525280f016cf71f2650df19fc602d84e7281ad7b chooses the server IP
more carefully.  This change refreshes the known server addresses before
looking for available IPs, removing a potential race during VM creation
that could result in "no addresses found".

Change-Id: I69d2c9f479d3a41944a211970c674923b4e7933a

commit_message:
Support manila shares as binary store

Changes to support manila shares as a binary store.
Oozie, Spark and Storm jobs can now run with job
binaries stored in manila shares.

Change-Id: I2f5fbe3d36ef4b87e5cadd337854e95ed95ebaa0
Implements: bp manila-as-binary-store

Also some small suggestions inline.'}, {'account_id': 11778, 'date': '2015-08-14 17:49:01.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 11778, 'date': '2015-08-14 17:57:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

(3 comments)

Timur,

Your comment is correct.  Responsive does not work on mobile out of the box.  Due to mobile devices having much higher resolution, media queries don't function as you would expect until we turn it on as a meta tag in the header: 

<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">

Because of that, I think it is outside the scope of this patch.

It still looks terrible on smaller mobile screens though (even with the above code).  As soon as the rest of the app is made responsive ready, we should open a ticket for it.

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-08-13 17:55:07.000000000', 'message': "Horizon Context Selection should be to the right

An unintended result of a recent refactor left the context picker css
without any love. The refactor of the topbar needs to have style
parity to its previous incantation.

It was noted that the design for the current context selection is not
a good pattern to follow for responsive design.  The menu grows
horizontally, which will make it difficult to see on smaller screens
as well as when it is displayed in the now responsive topbar.  The
original design still applies to larger screens, but now on smaller
screens, the menu will fall back to a vertically growing responsive
menu.

The nav-header color has been changed, because it was also the same
color as the 'disabled' nav item state, which was confusing.

Change-Id: I6e7c7b6fed08d215bcf83941da1bf90b40cd17b2
closes-bug: #1483910
partially implements bp: bootstrap-html-standards

commit_message:
Horizon Context Selection should be to the right

An unintended result of a recent refactor left the context picker css
without any love. The refactor of the topbar needs to have style
parity to its previous incantation.

It was noted that the design for the current context selection is not
a good pattern to follow for responsive design.  The menu grows
horizontally, which will make it difficult to see on smaller screens
as well as when it is displayed in the now responsive topbar.  The
original design still applies to larger screens, but now on smaller
screens, the menu will fall back to a vertically growing responsive
menu.

The nav-header color has been changed, because it was also the same
color as the 'disabled' nav item state, which was confusing.

Refactoring of the some of the context_selection.py code was required
in order to support wrapping the menus in <li> tagss without needing
to change their corresponding HTML files.  Since the files can be
used as templatetag templates outside of _header.html, it was best to
keep them as stand alone <ul> lists.

Change-Id: I6e7c7b6fed08d215bcf83941da1bf90b40cd17b2
closes-bug: #1483910
partially implements bp: bootstrap-html-standards

commit_message:
Fix image owner can't be changed issue in v2

It is incompatible with v1 for owner change in v2. Image owner
should be able to be changed, and only by admin user. This patch
fixes the issue and add some test cases for that.

Closes-Bug: #1420008

Change-Id: Ief9dc3329d7df07e1da32bb5ccc557096f73624f

[{'created': '2015-08-14 23:43:02.000000000', 'message': 'Fixes Master IP address for kube-proxy

Previously, kube-proxy was using 127.0.0.1 to communicate with
the k8s master. Since kube-proxy runs on nodes, this address
is insufficient and causes kube-proxy to not work with the
following error:

Unable to load services: \
Get http://127.0.0.1:8080/api/v1beta3/services: \
dial tcp 127.0.0.1:8080: connection refused

Fixes bug 1485143

Change-Id: I51a3f12126acc9ba564a8ace6a73852945ed9d5b
'}, {'created': '2015-08-16 22:54:00.000000000', 'message': 'Provides correct master IP address for kube-proxy

read by the kube-proxy service. This change adds the KUBE_MASTER
configuration parameter to /etc/kubernetes/config.

Closes-Bug: #1485143

Change-Id: I51a3f12126acc9ba564a8ace6a73852945ed9d5b
'}]
commit_message:
Provides correct master IP address for kube-proxy

Previously, KUBE_MASTER was not being set in a config file
read by the kube-proxy service. This change adds the KUBE_MASTER
configuration parameter to /etc/kubernetes/config.

Closes-Bug: #1485143

Change-Id: I51a3f12126acc9ba564a8ace6a73852945ed9d5b

commit_message:
Drop unused Neutron extensions

These extensions are unmaintained and have accumulated siginifcant
bitrot.  Neutron upstream has changed how extensions work and now
these unused things are starting to cause problems.  Remove them until
we can rebase them on the current Neutron code and repair them.

Change-Id: I627bb0b878d4c6fccca1a7abad242df41ed29698
Closes-bug: #1481463

commit_message:
Ensure a http 405 is returned on container(s) PUT

Added the template='json' option to the pecan expose decorator on
the index function on the Containers controller to ensure that we
pass control to that function rather than have pecan determine
that some content type(s) aren't what it expects.

Without this fix, pecan looks at the content type (we set as
application/json) and since its not "text/html" pecan returns an
http 406 rather than passing control on to the index function which
sets the more appropriate http 405.

Closes-Bug #1485157

Change-Id: I4ff640c7bd412b9946797d2da7be04fe78678c63

commit_message:
Improve help messages

Help messages are in normally fully sentences starting with a capital
letter, some of the help messages follow this but not all. Adjust all so
that help messages look consistent.

Also, improve wording of --help text.

Change-Id: Ia22ccc42d71a4c9d7085303939dae9948ba52418

commit_message:
Don't update instances that will be removed

Now handle_update in instance_group has such logic:
updating the instances and then resizing group to desired
number of resources. In the case of reducing the number of
resources we make update for resources that will be deleted
at resize. So first do resize to such size that satisfy
both desired capacity after whole update and effct_capacity
(some resources can be added during rolling_update
to satisfy min_in_service parameter).

Change-Id: I51a8b42358efc25422cf0b384b3a08ab5fa4910f

commit_message:
Fix sample config file generation

There's a import missing and oslo-config-generator expects
"oslo.config.opts" as namespace to search for configuration options.

Change-Id: Ib1b3fef9340a8932e8a0a7aacf6dc92ad7a32ab7
Closes-bug: #1485526

Change-Id: I2daadd969383aaf49ad87876ba108dd80dd56f08
"}, {'created': '2015-08-09 00:07:41.000000000', 'message': "Use oslo_utils reflection to get 'f' callable name

Using the utility function gets a better name.

For example:

$ python

>>> from oslo_utils import reflection
>>> class A(object):
...   def m(self):
...     pass
... 
>>> z = A()

Change-Id: I2daadd969383aaf49ad87876ba108dd80dd56f08
"}]
commit_message:
Use oslo_utils reflection to get 'f' callable name

Using the utility function gets a better name.

For example:

$ python

>>> from oslo_utils import reflection
>>> class A(object):
...   def m(self):
...     pass
... 
>>> z = A()
>>> reflection.get_callable_name(z.m)
'__main__.A.m'

Versus:

>>> z.m.__name__
'm'

Change-Id: I2daadd969383aaf49ad87876ba108dd80dd56f08

commit_message:
Expose a 'rpm_version' extra command

Intended usage, getting a rpm *compatible* version number from pbr
from a pbr using python package. Typically this will then get
put into a rpm spec file (what is used to build an rpm) and used to
build an rpm using `rpmbuild` (the thing used to translate rpm spec
files into rpms).

For example: this allows [1][2] (which I am the primary maintainer of
and godaddy, cray, and y! are users of) to get out of the whacky
and/or flakey rpm version number calculation/conversion process (which
previously just worked around by saying only use tags).

[1] https://github.com/stackforge/anvil
[2] https://anvil.readthedocs.org/en/latest/topics/summary.html

Change-Id: I26cd1d6e8aef69d52e8a4f36bd264c690e712ba3

commit_message:
Have the enforcer have its own file cache

Instead of having a library have a global (and not garbage
collectable) file cache that is only used by enforcers and
no other code have the file cache be per-enforcer so that it
can be garbage collected when the enforcer drops from the
scope its used in.

This also removes one more usage of global state with instance
specific state, which makes things easier to test and easier
to isolate problems in (the less things that can be 'touched
at a distance' the better).

Change-Id: I208b08ae00e0337b594ece0f2b335d4de9f7392b

commit_message:
Export Zones

Modified export zones to improve time.
Initially took 6 minutes 30 seconds to export a zone with 30,000
recordsets. Now takes 2-4 seconds. To export a zone with 100,000
recordsets, it now takes approximately 7-16 seconds.

MySQL Dump with 2 big zones (30,000 recordsets and 100,000 recordsets)
http://goo.gl/CEZ3pT

WIP

Change-Id: Ifc079ec89b7190532c90e1edb0e70f8d3da0018e

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-06-22 01:44:45.000000000', 'message': 'OpenStack: Purge disabled code that reads arbitrary files

There is some half-existing code in the OpenStack serverprovider for a
"userdata_file" option that reads userdata from a file path.  Currently
this feature doesn't work because:

A) The config schema rejects the userdata_file property.

B) There's a bug where the file contents are only passed to the first
   server created (should use a string rather than a file handle in the
   loop below).

Since security bugs that allow reading arbitrary files from OpenStack
servers are all the rage these days, this change removes the vestigial
userdata_file code to prevent anyone being tempted to "fix" this feature
and allow reads from arbitrary server-side paths in some distant future.

If/when this feature is desired, it needs to be clear that the
userdata_file contents will be read on the client side of some
hypothetical client/server split (ie: in the CLI).

Change-Id: Id0134f7a1087bf62886b889b8a84f1cc5abeeeac

commit_message:
OpenStackProvider: Purge disabled code that reads arbitrary files

There is some half-existing code in the OpenStack serverprovider for a
"userdata_file" option that reads userdata from a file path.  Currently
this feature doesn't work because:

A) The config schema rejects the userdata_file property.

B) There's a bug where the file contents are only passed to the first
   server created (should use a string rather than a file handle in the
   loop below).

This change removes the vestigial userdata_file code to prevent anyone
being tempted to "fix" this feature and allowing reading of arbitrary
server-side files in some distant future.

If/when this feature is desired, it needs to be clear that the
userdata_file contents will be read on the client side of some
hypothetical client/server split (ie: in the CLI).

Closes-Bug: #1484309
Change-Id: Id0134f7a1087bf62886b889b8a84f1cc5abeeeac

commit_message:
VNX driver needs extra params for create cg from src

The cinder manager is passing 2 additional parameters (source_cg and
source_vols) to create_consistencygroup_from_src of driver. VNX
driver needs to add these 2 parameters.

Change-Id: Ibf1ac8955238a27c82b32e1aa728f1efacd71273
Closes-Bug: #1482571

commit_message:
Allow Tempest to skip snapshot tests

On last midcycle meetup was decided to make snapshots optional feature.
So, at first step, add possibility to skip all functional tests that
use snapshots.

Partially implements bp snapshots-optional

Change-Id: Ib7dd3303e3974298439b6ac543b9df628b69e6ae

subject: Added WEBROOT to websso origin url Correct websso origin url in case of dashboard not on / but on different WEBROOT. The general case is when dashboard answers at http://{HOST_IP}/dashboard, in this case the origin url must be http://{HOST_IP}/dashboard/auth/websso and not http://{HOST_IP}/auth/websso.

commit_message:
Added WEBROOT to websso origin url
Correct websso origin url in case of dashboard not on / but on different WEBROOT.
The general case is when dashboard answers at http://{HOST_IP}/dashboard, in this case the origin url must be http://{HOST_IP}/dashboard/auth/websso and not http://{HOST_IP}/auth/websso.

Change-Id: I5b1dd1e5c19bb13b5c060c384f4c5f0825632fde

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-07-21 19:59:15.000000000', 'message': "Fix deleting instance with attached volume

If you failed to boot an instance from volume or with attached volume
by any external reason then you will fail to delete it because cinder
doesn't have this volume attached while nova thinks that volume is
attached.

We can fix it by taking into account InvalidInput exception we get
from cinder.

Change-Id: Ibdcb870aff1a59948136f1f9c3e30390e7f081b0
Closes-bug: 1476806
"}, {'created': '2015-07-23 15:08:07.000000000', 'message': "Fix deleting instance with incorrectly attached volume

If you failed to boot an instance with attached volume by any external reason then you will fail to delete it because cinder doesn't have this volume attached while nova thinks that it is.

We can fix it by taking into account InvalidInput exception we get from
cinder in such cases. We already ignore the DiskNotFound and VolumeNotFound
cases during delete.

Change-Id: Ibdcb870aff1a59948136f1f9c3e30390e7f081b0
Closes-bug: 1476806

commit_message:
Fix deleting instance with incorrectly attached volume

If you failed to boot an instance with attached volume by any external
reason then you will fail to delete it because cinder doesn't have this
volume attached while nova thinks that it is.

We can fix it by taking into account newly added NoActiveAttachments
exception that is thrown when we get InvalidInput exception
from cinder, that comes along with specific 'Invalid volume: Detach
volume failed, because there are currently no active attachments'
error message. We already ignore the DiskNotFound and VolumeNotFound
cases during delete, thus this is just a new case.

There is a change pending I9aebe01ad4548e169a32995bf40722fcab0c26b0
with a long term fix.

Change-Id: Ibdcb870aff1a59948136f1f9c3e30390e7f081b0
Closes-bug: 1476806

commit_message:
GPFS volume encryption-at-rest support

This patch extends the capability of gpfs driver to support volume encryption
at rest using GPFS Native Encryption feature (https://ibm.biz/BdXPBm).

This includes:
1. Verification of configured gpfs backend to support encryption at rest.
2. Driver exposes gpfs_encryption_rest capability via volume type convention.

Usage - Cloud admin creates a volume type "encrypted" with extra-specs
  gpfs_encryption_rest=True
Every volume created using type "encrypted", the volumes will be encrypted
at rest.

DocImpact

Needs an update in gpfs driver documentation, as this patch introduces
encrypted backend support.

Change-Id: I83949ca51668834ecbce52e90527cf06f95bd001
Implements: blueprint gpfs-volume-encryption-rest

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-08-13 22:36:46.000000000', 'message': 'Fixed translation in python modal templates

In several dialogs there is untranslatable text. These dialogs were
translatable in kilo. The path added in the configuration was not adequate.

Change-Id: Ib2b5592d8e01084fcfd91c6d7912fc91766585d2
Closes-Bug: #1481045
'}]
commit_message:
Fixed translation in python modal templates

In several dialogs there is untranslatable text. These dialogs were
translatable in kilo. The path added in the configuration was not adequate.

Change-Id: Ib2b5592d8e01084fcfd91c6d7912fc91766585d2
Closes-Bug: #1481045

[{'created': '2015-08-14 20:30:06.000000000', 'message': 'Support extend_share in NetApp cDOT drivers

Now that extend_share is in Manila core, we can support the new API in
the NetApp cDOT drivers.  As this patch adds methods to the driver shim
layer, also add a unit test to ensure the shims remain in sync for each
cDOT driver.

Implements: blueprint extend-share-in-netapp-cdot-drivers
Change-Id: I407a12a0cd44f37a62bd500251049c50a097f2c4
'}]
commit_message:
Support extend_share in NetApp cDOT drivers

Now that extend_share is in Manila core, we can support the new API in
the NetApp cDOT drivers.  As this patch adds methods to the driver shim
layer, also add a unit test to ensure the shims remain in sync for each
cDOT driver.

Implements: blueprint extend-share-in-netapp-cdot-drivers
Change-Id: I407a12a0cd44f37a62bd500251049c50a097f2c4

commit_message:
Configure keystone v3 for nova

Identity API v3 was added to kilo. This patch changes
v3 endpoints from http://127.0.0.1:8774/v3 to actual proto://IP:Port/v3
schema.

Co-Authored-By: Sergii Golovatiuk <sgolovatiuk@mirantis.com>

Related-Bug: #1479320
Closes-Bug: #1481296

Change-Id: I5ade31e5b30259cec76471ef932254e8e45cac22

Add code to ensure VEM uplink ports are brought up and brought up on boot.

commit_message:
N1KV VEM module doesn't ensure uplink ports are up

Add code to ensure VEM uplink ports are brought up and brought up on boot.
There can be anywhere from 0 to 8 uplink ports configured, so there are 8
sections added to configure these ports. Duplicated the code as some
versions of puppet don't seem to support iteration.

Change-Id: I8e661708f65b35b73d9154b78467d76ed41eda53
Closes-Bug: 1479520

commit_message:
Add EnvironmentDescription objects to fullstack

The EnvironmentDescription class describes an entire fullstack
environment (as opposed to the currently implemented host-only
descriptions). This will allow future patches to signify that a test
should set up an environment that supports tunneling, l2pop, QoS and
more.

Change-Id: If21a0979a3760e374b9beb36aac8b2f4b90a02c9

commit_message:
Add a fullstack fake VM, basic connectivity test

* Full stack tests fake VMs are represented via a namespace,
  MAC, IP address and default gateway. They're plugged to an OVS
  bridge via an OVS internal port. As opposed to the current
  fake machine class used in functional testing, this new fake
  machine also creates a Neutron port via the API and sets the
  IP and MAC according to it. It also sets additional attributes
  on the OVS port to allow the OVS agent to do its magic.
* The functional fake machine and the full stack fake machine
  should continue to share commonalities.
* The fullstack fake machine currently takes the IP address
  from the port and statically assigns it to the namespace
  device. Later when I'll add support for the DHCP agent
  in full stack testing this assignment will look for the dhcp
  attribute of the subnet and either assign the IP address
  via 'ip' or call a dhcp client.
* The fullstack fake machine currently uses the existing
  PortFixture, so it plugs directly to br-int. In order to
  support security groups
* Added a basic L2 connectivity test between two such machines
  on the same Neutron network, with 3 different environments
  (VLANs, tunnels without l2pop and tunnels with l2pop). Since
  basic L2 connectivity is covered I switched the L3 HA test
  to run only with tunnels.

Change-Id: Id673cc75ac2b18c1a9c8add781859a723ae7175a

[{'account_id': 12693, 'date': '2015-07-15 12:44:55.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 12693, 'date': '2015-07-15 12:45:57.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 12320, 'date': '2015-07-15 12:56:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Instead of keep downloading lots of packages in the form of giant tarballs, can't we please use online repositories, install the precise versions needed, and remove the online repositories?

This would allow packages to be properly cached by dib (unlike with a giant tarball, which you have to manually care about), and download less unneeded stuff from mapr servers. 

Not also considering that keeping a local repository with all the packages creates a big guest image, which will also need lot of time to get started (as packages need to be installed) every time."}, {'account_id': 12693, 'date': '2015-07-15 13:27:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Unfortunately, we can't install packages during image build phase. MapR installation is tricky. A lot of things happens in post-install scripts. Several ecosystem packages require  started cluster. In general, to implement your approach we need to configure and start cluster during image building and gracefully shut it down. Consequently, we need to change current plugin implementation to start clusters from such images. I agree that local repo is not the best solution, but the only improvement which can be made is to download packages directly instead of a tarball."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-07-15 14:53:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

(3 comments)

Well, in this merge request you are already making sure there's one (or at most two) version for each of the packages you are installing. Thus, you can
- just install the packages of which you have one single version
- download only the ones (using yumdownload, apt-get download, etc, so from the online repository) you have more than one version
this will hopefully give a smaller image, make sure there's no need to download 6GB and more of packages, whose majority is going to be removed.

Also, I'd say that would be good if you can work on the mapr scenarios in sahara-ci-config, as the only one currently fails, so we have no automated way to check for validity in changes to mapr images generation.

Left also some technical comments which apparently were eaten when commenting earlier..."}, {'account_id': 6786, 'date': '2015-07-28 09:36:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Added ability to specify exact package versions for MapR

List of improvements:
1. Ecosystem repo is downloaded from repo instead of giant tar archive
2. Mapping of MapR packages moved from python script to separate json file
3. Versions of packages to keep are specified exactly instead of "several last versions"
4. Versions of packages to keep are specified in separate json files for each MapR version
5. Code for repo creating moved to separate script
6. curl and tar invocations merged together
7. Resources aren't copied to image
8. Removed unreachable code
9. Hive 0.12 was removed from remote repo so now it's removed from package list

Change-Id: I93ad9be3b02d5a2f6f0e4c13303ecce7ba32c84b
Implements: blueprint mapr-versions

commit_message:
Add iptables rule to neutron agents containers

When running in an AIO environment, we need to drop an iptables rule to
ensure that communication between instances and the neutron metadata
service works.

Change-Id: Icc081fe83712ce883baa88f99db60c52dcc4c1ae
Closes-Bug: #1483603
(cherry picked from commit d879994e13e788123e2db1368b985d0e5fe9cb1b)

commit_message:
Replace python-ldap with ldap3 library

The python-ldap library is being preplaced by ldap3 in other
OpenStack projects.  It helps us get ready for Python3.  This
commit makes this change, and fixes some associated unit tests.

Change-Id: I061ae6827cae9a43601f05425082a397267f6087
Partially-Implements: blueprint barbican-py3

commit_message:
Add deactivate step to extend_lv

Extending a linear LVM volume that has a snapshot requires
that the LV be deactivated explicitly prior to extending.

This adds a deactivate_lv method and calls it prior to
issuing the extend call. If auto_activation_volume_list
is not defined lvm.conf, then volumes will be reactivated
automatically after the extend.  If auto_activation_volume_list
is defined, then volumes that should be automatically
reactivated should be added to the auto_activation_volume_list
or they won't be activated automatically.
NOTE: This doesn't apply to thin provisioned LVs as they don't
require the deactivation step.

DocImpact: When a user extends LVM Volumes with a snapshot, the
volumes will be deactivated.  Their re-activation is automatic,
unless auto_activation_volume_list is defined in lvm.conf.
See lvm.conf for more info.  Thin provisioned LVM Volumes
will not be deactivated as they don't require it.

Conflicts:
        cinder/tests/brick/test_brick_lvm.py
        cinder/tests/unit/test_srb.py

Co-Authored-By: John Griffith <john.griffith8@gmail.com>
Change-Id: If746625cfe658c3528525dc7f4bf869f1c9704dc
Closes-Bug: #1470558
(cherry picked from commit 314611f79afa6fe79f3d5022c814772048669bb0)

commit_message:
Revert "Revert "Use the correct auth_plugin for token authentication""

Name the auth type needed for using an admin token "admin_token". This
hack can be removed with keystoneclient and/or keystoneauth make a
release with the admin_token entrypoint defined.

Naming it admin_token further reduces the conflict with OSC, which
should make the patch to work around OSC having different arguments
unnecessary.

This reverts commit 0e3117cb01d201f403be72cbb1218b9eec69a541.

Change-Id: I079c7c61b2637ded73542876cb1378a0731f8631

commit_message:
Log warning instead of raising RuntimeError

Changes introduced in:
I0fc1717e3118bc1cd7b9cd0ccc072251cfb2c038

are causing Neutron to fail as summarized by Doug in:
http://markmail.org/message/2xlclp7gqnqpkted

So we should log warnings instead and make sure we
find which projects are affected (using logstash) and
fix them. Once we do that, then we can switch this
back to raise RuntimeError(s)

Change-Id: I9dce272246b89f3ec63aefcf11d385fd2d21da6e

commit_message:
Load maximum unique key identifier from DB

When plugin starts, query the db for all logical ports
and find the highest unique key that was allocated.
Set the global id to be this maximum and next allocation
will use it

Change-Id: I22bc828ec190d05d2cb6731bd9be06a4edd5654c
Closes-Bug: #1485501

commit_message:
Do not dump HealthcheckResult class source

If verbose is true, the class definition is printed just
before being built. We don't really need to print this into
our logs, so we should drop the verbose parameter (as it
defaults to False anyway).

Closes-Bug: #1482744
Change-Id: Ic6cb7fe9c87151bb0c318d060fd88bb2e1977404

commit_message:
Return CPU frequency as int vs. float

The general expectation is that CPU frequency is returned as an int
vs. a floating type (e.g., see libvirt) for the driver's host CPU
stats. This patch covers that as well as a simple test case assert.

Change-Id: Icd47e82c07fc2e9bf8973a7ee3c46886a3021c34
Closes-Bug: 1485341

commit_message:
Delete DHCP port from DB on network delete

DHCP port deletion is not sent to the Neutron plugin upon
deletion of network.
this fix find the relevant network ports and delets them in the
DB.

ImageCache.fetch_image became quite complicated function, here are the things it does:

* If only master_path (cached image path) exists, check
  if it is up to date with href contents and link
  dest_path to it, if out of date re-download;

* If only dest_path exists, it is removed and image is
  downloaded;

* If both exist, their inode numbers are equal and
  master_path modification time is greater than href
  modification time then everything is up to date (for
  glance images only inode numbers should be checked as
  updated_at attribute represents time when image
  metadata was updated, not its contents);

* If both exist, master_path modification time is 
  greater than href modification time but master_path
  inode number != dest_path inode number, update hard
  link only;

* If both exist and master_path modification time is
  less than href modification time then cache is out of
  date, remove both master_path and dest_path.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-25 16:51:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-06-24 09:57:21.000000000', 'message': "Update cached images based on update time

Currently, if non-glance image is used in ironic, and contents of this
image are updated on HTTP(S) server or on FS available locally (except
for the case when it is the FS where image cache is located), ironic
won't be able to determine that the image was updated and will not
update the cache.

In this cahnge it is proposed to use last modification date to
determine if an image is up to date. For FS it can accomplished with
standard OS means, and for HTTP(S) images 'Last-Modified' HTTP header
can be used.

Closes-bug: #1459328
Change-Id: Ia3e6b6072fdf7a4bfffdc3fbaf31103605c7ff5b

commit_message:
Update cached images based on update time

Currently, if non-glance image is used in ironic, and contents of this
image are updated on HTTP(S) server or on file system available
locally (except for the case when it is the file system where image
cache is located), ironic won't be able to determine that the image
was updated and will not update the cache.

In this change it is proposed to use last modification date to
determine if an image is up to date. For file system it can be
accomplished with standard operating system means, and for HTTP(S)
images 'Last-Modified' HTTP header can be used.

Closes-bug: #1459328
Change-Id: Ia3e6b6072fdf7a4bfffdc3fbaf31103605c7ff5b

[{'created': '2015-08-11 07:06:41.000000000', 'message': "return request_id in case of 500 error

Request-id is not getting returned if glance throws 500 error
because context middleware 'process_response' method is not
getting called.

Catching generic exception in wsgi Resource class, and returning
'webob.exc.HTTPInternalServerError' object as response.
Context middleware adds request-id header to this response object.

Closes-Bug: #1480196

Change-Id: I5ed9f64e07c5624f816088113ff67cb03cc8e3f2
"}]
commit_message:
return request_id in case of 500 error

Request-id is not getting returned if glance throws 500 error
because context middleware 'process_response' method is not
getting called.

Catching generic exception in wsgi Resource class, and returning
'webob.exc.HTTPInternalServerError' object as response.
Context middleware adds request-id header to this response object.

Closes-Bug: #1480196

Change-Id: I5ed9f64e07c5624f816088113ff67cb03cc8e3f2

commit_message:
Don't use slashes for long lines - use parentheses instead

According to the OpenStack Style Guidelines [1] it is prefered to wrap
long lines in parentheses and not a backslash for line continuation. As
we are following those guidelines in our project - this patch replaces
backslash with parentheses for line continuation.

_[1] http://docs.openstack.org/developer/hacking/#general

Co-Authored-By: Roman Vasilets <rvasilets@mirantis.com>
Co-Authored-By: Kamil Rykowski <kamil.rykowski@intel.com>

Change-Id: I1743a539703c964277b0e8da203ee46bc8014fb5
Closes-bug: 1394605

commit_message:
Exclude event type from targets of alarm evaluator

The new evaluator service will be added to handle 'event' type alarms
only. Existing evaluator have to exclude those 'event' type alarms
from their targets which will be evaluated periodically.

Change-Id: Ia501771ee8d3dcd424c7e415d8aeb3d41a8e8de0
Implements: blueprint event-alarm-evaluator

commit_message:
jenkins/copy_puppet_logs.sh: prepare apache_config dir

This patch aims to manage apache_config directory before copying
apache configuration from /etc.
Otherwise, the job will fail since apache_config dir does not
exist.

Change-Id: Iafd27e9edf8865e462d4e33a2514afc8c466e290

commit_message:
Add a Distinct Exception for Exceeding Max Retries

There are two separate and very different situations which raise a
NoValidHost exception when attempting to spawn a new VM, which is
confusing for operators who need to determine why a VM failed to spawn.
This proposes to add a new exception class that will make the two
failure modes more obvious to the operators.

Blueprint: no-valid-host-reporting

Change-Id: I1d6784249ff5c99d1a370d046d9078bb250e0974

commit_message:
acceptance: enable debug & verbosity for OpenStack logs

Enable debug & verbose when possible for OpenStack services logs, so we can read a maximum
of informations in Jenkins jobs logs and easily debug our eventual failures.

Change-Id: I62b8510442a747d2f909bdceb0717839c9778e6d

commit_message:
Full response for v1 ImageClient methods

Provide the entire response object, not just the images, for the
tempest v1 glance client's create_image, update_image and list_images
methods. This is all the work necessary to implement the blueprint
referenced below on this client as the remaining methods already
return the full response.

partially implements: blueprint method-return-value-and-move-service-clients-to-lib
Change-Id: Ia52bfde7cef1420c0c7d94288154fe4b6d54cd5f

commit_message:
Support placeholders in args of job for i/o

Several job types (at least spark) can require having url of input
or output data in arguments of job execution. The aim of the patch
is to add support of testing such types of job executions.
Now you can add {input_datasource} or {output_datasource}
into args of template of job execution, and that will be replaced
with corresponding urls.

Change-Id: I816ca6b559e3878c97f7d8d5088e0b458a19bd1b

commit_message:
Add recommendation support to Cloudera plugin

Added support of recommendations to both versions of Cloudera
plugin. Also added small refactoring in AutoConfigsProvider.

Partial-Implements blueprint: recommend-configuration

Change-Id: I25f906d830b803b65ffcc7443978ea3cfef126da

commit_message:
Use min and max on IntOpt option types

Latest version of oslo.config support the ability to set valid
range on IntOpt option values.  This path makes use of that feature
for a number of options with well known minimum and maximum values.

Change-Id: I26c920a2be68deeaa6ba534eb9d92b2960f78328

commit_message:
Move initializing globals to stackrc

Having global initialization in functions-common prohibits
enabling multiple plugins. If a plugin sources functions-common in
it's plugin.sh the globals will be reinitialized as local variables
and will orverride global ones and will prevent execution of other plugins.
Moving initialization to stackrc resolves this issue.

Closes-Bug: #1469178
Change-Id: Ib187d188ffa99d696e77eda7b9106ba3b66919d7

[{'created': '2015-08-04 16:01:15.000000000', 'message': "Return a specific exception for detach fails when no attachments

Nova change Ibdcb870aff1a59948136f1f9c3e30390e7f081b0 is fixing a bug
where boot from volume fails to attach a volume but the instance can't
be deleted because detach fails since there are no attachments, so the
instance is not deletable via the compute API.

As part of the nova fix, the InvalidVolume error message returned from
the volume API is being parsed to see if nova can safely ignore the
failure and continue with deleting the instance. It's preferable that
cinderclient is raising the specific exception so nova can just handle
that without having to parse any error messages coming back from the
volume API.

This change adds the specific exception type checking to cinderclient
for this specific 400 error response. It is written in a generic enough
way that we can build other exception handling in later if needed using
regex pattern checking since we don't necessarily want a one-to-one
mapping of the exceptions coming out of cinder to what's checked in the
client since that's fairly brittle.

Partial-Bug: #1476806

Change-Id: I9aebe01ad4548e169a32995bf40722fcab0c26b0

commit_message:
Return a specific exception for detach fails when no attachments

Nova change Ibdcb870aff1a59948136f1f9c3e30390e7f081b0 is fixing a bug
where boot from volume fails to attach a volume but the instance can't
be deleted because detach fails since there are no attachments, so the
instance is not deletable via the compute API.

As part of the nova fix, the InvalidVolume error message returned from
the volume API is being parsed to see if nova can safely ignore the
failure and continue with deleting the instance. It's preferable that
cinderclient is raising the specific exception so nova can just handle
that without having to parse any error messages coming back from the
volume API.

This change adds the specific exception type checking to cinderclient
for this specific 400 error response. It is written in a generic enough
way that we can build other exception handling in later if needed using
regex pattern checking since we don't necessarily want a one-to-one
mapping of the exceptions coming out of cinder to what's checked in the
client since that's fairly brittle.

Partial-Bug: #1476806

Change-Id: I9aebe01ad4548e169a32995bf40722fcab0c26b0

commit_message:
Add prepare snapshots for OS upgrade procedure

Implements blueprint: system-tests-for-openstack-upgrades-feature

Add two tests:
1) Deploy cluster with HA mode, neutron VLAN,
ceph for all, Ubuntu
2) Upgrade master node with deployed cluster

Change-Id: I58940eefbe107e65d44ed599a34e51733b37ff4c

commit_message:
WIP: Locks in manager with Tooz

This patch replaces and adds synchronized decorator to some method that
was missing it and replaces oslo's synchronized decorator in a couple of
methods as well.

For this lock methods have been added to Cinder Versioned Objects and
synchronized decorator has been extended to support multiple locks in
the same decorator call and the possibility to use the new Cinder
Versioned Objects lock methods.

This is part of a PoC for HA A-A

Change-Id: I7ed3097ff25e01c3a91c5552c45cde7a1ca7f9b7

[{'created': '2015-08-04 10:15:24.000000000', 'message': "Set identical 'host' for all nova-compute services

Evacuate cleanup mechanism destroys all locally running instances on
nova-compute service startup if instance.host is not equal to host where
nova-compute is starting ('host' configuration stanza in [DEFAULT]);
this situation is desirable for KVM/QEMU hypervisors when nova-compute
manages local instances, but it is dangerous when remote hypervisor is
used (e.g. vCenter); to avoid such behaviour we need to configure same
value for 'host' stanza on all available controller nodes to avoid
instances stoppage when nova-compute service is migrated by pacemaker
from one controller to another.

Change-Id: If464593449110c326054adff21be05b1ca1e2b65
DocImpact: document as known issue for 6.0
Closes-bug: #1463977
"}]
commit_message:
Set identical 'host' for all nova-compute services

Evacuate cleanup mechanism destroys all locally running instances on
nova-compute service startup if instance.host is not equal to host where
nova-compute is starting ('host' configuration stanza in [DEFAULT]);
this situation is desirable for KVM/QEMU hypervisors when nova-compute
manages local instances, but it is dangerous when remote hypervisor is
used (e.g. vCenter); to avoid such behaviour we need to configure same
value for 'host' stanza on all available controller nodes to avoid
instances stoppage when nova-compute service is migrated by pacemaker
from one controller to another.

Change-Id: If464593449110c326054adff21be05b1ca1e2b65
DocImpact: document as known issue for 6.0
Closes-bug: #1463977

It's too late in the cycle to merge something like this now. However, I suspect we should probably make this part of the internal plugin API refactoring. This is one of several issues with internal plugins being able to get handles directly to other plugins.

For example, we don't have a nice place to put callback processing or notifications that are supposed to be applied after a certain plugin method is called without having login in the plugin itself.

[{'created': '2014-10-21 02:42:47.000000000', 'message': 'internal callers of create_{network, subnet, port} ignore extension

The calling convention of plugin create_{network, subnet, port} is
all the necessary argument are filled with default value dynamically.
Which arguments are necessary depends on resource extension which
core plugin supports.
On the other hand, internal direct caller of those methods ignore those
conventions so that adding extension causes exception like key error
of argument.
This patch introduces helper function to fix up argument and replace
the caller of those methods.

Change-Id: Ibc6ff897a1a00665a403981a218100a698eb1c33

The calling convention of plugin create_{network, subnet, port} is
the necessary default arguments are filled properly.
Which arguments are necessary depends on resource extension that
core plugin supports.
On the other hand, internal direct callers of those methods ignore those
conventions so that adding extension causes exception like key error
of argument.
This patch introduces helper functions to fix up arguments and replaces
the callers of those methods.

The intention is to replace all the callers, but there are two exceptions.
- Metaplugin: just passes through arguments to underlying plugin. so no
  need to check it again.
- n1kv plugging driver: passes extra argument n1kv:profile_id which isn't
  defined in api spec. It's quite plugin specific and I don't know what
  to be done so that I'll leave it to someone else who are familiar with it
  with the comment in the code.

commit_message:
Replace internal calls of create_{network, subnet, port}

When API controller calls method create_{network, subnet, port),
it made sure that the necessary default values for attrs are filled properly
according to attr mapping.

However, internal calls to these methods do not follow the convention,
when extension codes miss these values, exceptions will be thrown.

This patch introduces helper functions to fix up arguments and replaces
the direct callers of those methods.

Co-Authored-By: gong yong sheng <gong.yongsheng@99cloud.net>
Co-Authored-By: yalei wang <yalei.wang@intel.com>

Change-Id: Ibc6ff897a1a00665a403981a218100a698eb1c33
Closes-Bug: #1383546

commit_message:
Redirect http horizon to https when https enabled

This change updates the haproxy configuration for horizon to redirect
http traffic to https when https is enabled to ensure that only https is
used. When ssl is not enabled, the horizon http endpoint is configured
as a regular horizon endpoint.

Change-Id: I2db1fce35d4686e746cc1753ceea5332ab1325cb
Closes-Bug: 1484580
DocImpact: Horizon via HTTP will only redirect to the HTTPS version if
SSL is enabled.

commit_message:
Fix unit test mocks for new mock release

The new mock release(1.1.0) broke some of the unit tests which
were using incorrect mock methods that do not really exist.

Before mock 1.1.0 using such incorrectly mocked methods would
silently pass -- but after the upgrade these (rightly) cause
errors that need to be fixed.

Change-Id: I35fbd142a199f5e5f39b7835fee0ac888dc9784b
Closes-Bug: 1473454

commit_message:
README.rst: generate-constraints requires -r option

It seems the requirements file must be specified when using the
generate-constraints utility.
This patch amends the README.rst file to reflect this, as it
currently appears to hint that the -r options default to
global-requirements.txt

Change-Id: I1b2d67f717e1050b11d974da69071b127dd864c8

messages:

- gate-aodh-python34 http://logs.openstack.org/43/210443/1/check/gate-aodh-python34/e7cb176/ : SUCCESS in 5m 01s'}, {'account_id': 6537, 'date': '2015-08-07 19:35:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

what's the issue with filtering on what we want rather than what we don't want?"}, {'account_id': 1894, 'date': '2015-08-08 06:49:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Just minor one I can guess.
There might be a risk on alarm coordination.
To get alarms by querying interested types, we have to make sure the list includes all alarm types except 'event'.
Otherwise the coordinator might ignore some alarms, and those alarms won't be evaluated by any evaluator.
This may happen while updating evaluator nodes in which an alarm type is added, removed or renamed.
The problem may happen even current implementation until all evaluators are updated, so it's not a big issue.


I can say the following options for excluting event alarm:

option 1) current patch set

option 2) filter out event alarm after get all alarms from DB <-- small cade change (no change on DB API), but uninterested alarms will be extracted from the DB

option 3) get alarms by querying interested alarm types in one DB acess <-- code change will be the same size as option 1 since we have to make get_alarms() accept alarm_types.

option 4) get alarms by querying interested alarm types in multiple DB acess <-- no change on DB API, but DB access  will increase five-fold


If this change seems too big, we can take option 2."}, {'account_id': 9562, 'date': '2015-08-09 09:25:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi,

As it is for filtering out the 'event' type alarms I'm not against of this direction.

The question is whether we would like to provide the possibility to the users to use these kind of filters (include, exclude)? Or is there any other purpose because of which it would still be better to filter on what is interesting as opposed to exclude what is not? Gordon what do you think?

Best Regards,
Ildiko"}, {'account_id': 1894, 'date': '2015-08-12 16:55:59.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-08-12 17:07:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

(1 comment)

i think it's much rarer to actually filter on what you don't want rather than what you do want, mainly because it's less specific and can lead to larger returns... that said, i don't want to hold back this patch just because we lack query support."}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2015-08-13 08:29:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Storage: add 'exclude' constraint to get_alarms()

This patch adds a new parameter 'exclude' to get_alarms() as a constraint
by which a caller can filter out uninteresting alarms.

Change-Id: I8ce1481eccfa916cf1fd8921d57ed529d5b5271a
Implements: blueprint event-alarm-evaluator

commit_message:
Avoid translating debug log

According to the OpenStack translation policy, available at
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/LoggingStandards, debug messages
should not be translated.

Change-Id: I143100500dcdf505827ac64750f94c78bf0299e9

commit_message:
Port cleanup on failed VM instance launch

Currently if a VM instance launch fails, stale VM ports are left behind

Change-Id: I12fcd8263af81b81f4512a95da6e42b08e2e41ec
Closes-Bug: 1423453
(cherry picked from commit 32d55a36f19a8f93492264105ccf6a0c72369847)

commit_message:
LVM Thin Provisioning auto-detect

Add the ability to set lvm_type=auto, which will
enable thin provisioning if the system supports it,
and the configured volume group either:
a) has a pool LV with the expected name or
b) has no LVs

This, along with thin-provisioning accounting, will
give a path to move toward thin LVM as the default.

DocImpact: new value 'auto' for option 'lvm_type'

Partial-Bug: #1472803

Change-Id: Idfc1cd749bfd7aec659ab8e80629cc506cd9797a

commit_message:
On Volume list only retrieve needed data from DB

Currently when there is no limit set on a volume list query we retrieve
all volumes and then limit them locally using osapi_max_limit.  Similar
thing happens when we are using the marker for next pages, we get all
volumes from that marker until the last volume and then limit it
locally.

We should be limiting it on the DB side so we only retrieve the data we
are actually going to return to the API caller.

This patch always limits the data retrieved from the DB and for the
offset to keep working as it was before we need to do the offset on the
DB side as well.

For reference some tests were performed:

On a deployment with 60,000 volumes, 370,000 volume_metadata items and
240,000 volume_glance_metadata items in cinder db.  Before the patch
this will use nearly 10G memory.  With the patch we will just use about
500M.

Co-Authored-By: wangxiyuan <wangxiyuan@huawei.com>
Closes-bug:#1483165i

commit_message:
Create and update project fail when using keystone V3

When using keystone V3, creating and update project always fails
with name of project is already used, although the name isn't
duplicated. The name validation should be handled by keystone.
In horizon, the conflict name error is caught and then displaying
the appropriate error message.

Change-Id: I88fddf9b18f67af812ae86b539ea28f5e3643a86
Closes-Bug: #1473277
Closes-Bug: #1462011
Closes-Bug: #1460804

Update single letter release names to full names

'Kilo' and 'Mitaka'.

commit_message:
Switched to Ubuntu 14.04 LTS (Trusty) base image

It looks like loop devices works differently with Vivid and it make
sense to use latest LTS release instead.

Closes-Bug: #1483085

[{'created': '2015-08-14 22:40:47.000000000', 'message': 'Incorrect Etcd Port for Flannel

Previously, the Flannel daemon was using port 4001 to communicate
with etcd. This caused flanneld not to start. Since other
services require flanneld, this caused a domino effect of
service failures.

This commit updated the etcd ports to 2379/2380, but
did not update the flanneld configuration file accordingly:

https://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/magnum/commit/?id=68bfde02ca1aa77b54657cf61dbe60b62f226748

Fixes bug 1485122

Change-Id: I0312b3670a6cc15e8dc60bb4509d429165469259

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-08-16 16:06:10.000000000', 'message': 'nailgun::cobbler: bootstrap: adjust network configuration timeout

live-boot assumes 15 sec is enough to setup the network interface
However some Ethernet cards might take (much) longer to initialize,
which causes a boot failure. To solve the issue set the timeout to
2 minutes by default, and make it configurable via the
BOOTSTRAP/ethdevice_timeout knob in astute.yaml

DocImpact: bootstrap configuration item: ethdevice_timeout
Closes-Bug: #1485188
Change-Id: I4ac18aa229f13a9283b9bb0b19f1ce36e43954da
'}]
commit_message:
nailgun::cobbler: bootstrap: adjust network configuration timeout

live-boot assumes 15 sec is enough to setup the network interface
However some Ethernet cards might take (much) longer to initialize,
which causes a boot failure. To solve the issue set the timeout to
2 minutes by default, and make it configurable via the
BOOTSTRAP/ethdevice_timeout knob in astute.yaml

DocImpact: bootstrap configuration item: ethdevice_timeout
Closes-Bug: #1485188
Change-Id: I4ac18aa229f13a9283b9bb0b19f1ce36e43954da

Update readme to match current state

Kolla has been through alot of change in the Liberty development
cycle.  Modify the README.md to specify our current direction.

Change-Id: I67d304b206312f5915085dd99d0201b1df44f7ec
